<FIRST>u a AM-FourShot 3rdLd-Writethru a0636 03-19 0743</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Four Shot, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0636,0758</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Children And Police Officer Shot By Man With Gun</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 6th graf `The person ...' to UPDATE with
report of teen-agers tossing stones at Proctor's car earlier Saturday,
punching and threatening him.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY STERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST ORANGE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gunman who neighbors said was harassed
regularly by teen-agers shot three young children at an apartment
building Saturday and then wounded a police officer before being
killed in a gun battle, authorities said.
   One of the children, Ivory Smith, 9, died at 9:50 p.m. Saturday
in the trauma center of University Hospital in Newark. She had
gunshot wounds to the head, said Bob Arnold, associate administrator
of the hospital.
   Of the two other children, boys aged 8 and 12, one remained
critical and the third was in stable condition at the hospital,
Arnold said. The administrator declined to identify the children,
citing the wishes of family members.
   ``We don't have a motive yet,'' Police Chief Edward Palardy told
reporters at the scene of the shootings. ``It looks like some sort
of disaster in there. A man appears to have gone berserk and started
shooting.''
   The gunman, identified as George Proctor, in his 40s, died at
4:10 p.m. of gunshot wounds, said Margaret Francois, assistant
director of nursing at East Orange General Hospital.
   ``The person that was involved, for whatever reason, became very
antagonistic when he returned home this afternoon,'' said West
Orange Mayor Sam Spina, who visited the scene.
   Two witnesses, Peter Anderson and Eric Green, said they saw
teen-age boys tossing stones at Proctor's Cadillac earlier Saturday
while he was driving in Orange, which borders West Orange. Anderson
and Green said Proctor left his car to confront the youths, and one
of the teen-agers punched him in the face and threatened him.
   The three children who were shot apparently had no connection to
the earlier incident, the witnesses said. Police said they had heard
reports of that incident but would not say whether it was a motive
in the shooting.
   One neighbor, a 15-year resident who said he went fishing
regularly with the gunman, said Proctor had been physically and
verbally harassed recently by teen-age boys in an increasingly
drug-infested neighborhood.
   ``His mind probably just snapped,'' said the neighbor, who added
that he would not give his name for fear of an attack on his family
by neighborhood youths. ``He's a nice guy. ... It's a shame this had
to happen to him.''
   One witness, Robert Gress, who lives across an intersection from
the apartment building in this New York suburb, said he was playing
solitaire in his home shortly before 3 p.m. when he heard gunfire
that ``sounded like firecrackers.''
   Gress said when he looked outside, he saw a young boy by a parked
car across the street screaming, ``The guy's a maniac.''
   Gress said he then saw a police car pull up to the corner, and
the gunman started shooting at the cruiser.
   He went to telephone police and when he returned to the window,
the gunman was lying on the ground and the police officer also lay
wounded on the ground.
   The police officer, who works for the Orange Police Department,
was not seriously injured, Spina said. He was admitted in stable
condition at Orange Memorial Hospital, said spokeswoman Gail Proctor.
   The officer was on a routine patrol of the neighborhood, which
lies on the border of West Orange and the city of Orange, when he
heard the gunshots and went to the scene, Spina said.
   Palardy said the identity of the officer was not immediately
available.
   Proctor first started shooting at a woman in a first floor
apartment, and police believe the gun misfired, allowing the woman
time to run into the bathroom.
   The gunman then shot a child in the apartment and went outside,
where he shot two more children, Spina said.The police officer hit
the gunman with four rounds, officials said.
   Residents of the neighborhood said crime there has worsened
recently, with older people forced to live in fear of drug-related
violence.
   ``The young teen-agers are jumping people all the time,'' said
Deidra Biggest, a 25-year-old resident who has lived in the area for
eight months. ``Houses are getting robbed and cars are getting
stolen.''
   ``It's getting worse all the time,'' said Michael Gorham, 26, who
has lived in the area for six months. ``It's crazy out there.''
</TEXT>
