<FIRST>r a AM-BoatingRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0619 03-19 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boating Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0619,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Boys Presumed Drowned in Rhode Island; One Hurt in Florida</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 6-10, `The unidentified ... by authorities' with
5 grafs to UPDATE with boy's name, surgery continued into night, teen-age
drivers of boat taken into custody. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Boating accidents Saturday left two boys missing and presumed
drowned in Providence, R.I., and another critically injured near
Miami, authorities said.
   In Providence, police saw two youths jump into the water from a
boat in Mashapaug Pond and try to swim to shore just as a
thunderstorm began pelting the area with rain, according to a police
spokesman, Lt. Paul Verrechia.
   A bystander jumped into the water and began swimming toward one
of the youths and was joined by a police officer, but the boy went
beneath the surface before the men could reach him, Verricchia said.
   The other boy, who was about 25 yards beyond the first, went
beneath the water as a uniformed officer and an off-duty police
officer climbed aboard the youths' boat and paddled towards him, the
spokesman said.
   Divers called off the search after four hours, but were expected
to resume Sunday morning, Verrechia said. No one had reported the
boys missing and their identities were not known, he said.
   In Florida, a boy suffered multiple cuts to his head and chest
after he fell off a jet ski and was run over by a boat driven by
teen-agers in the Intracoastal Waterway, authorities said.
   Ami Missika, 5, was hit at about 3:30 p.m. EST after he fell into
the water in north Dade County, authorities said.
   The child, who was airlifted to Jackson Memorial Hospital,
underwent surgery ``well into the night'' and was in critical
condition, said Mark Santo, a hospital spokesman.
   ``He had lacerations to the head and the body from the
propeller,'' Santo said.
   The boat left the scene of the accident but returned later, said
Capt. Mike Lamphear of the Florida Marine Patrol. The teen-agers,
ranging from 13 to 15 years old, were taken into custody for
questioning, he said.
</TEXT>
