<FIRST>r i BC-Salva`or     03-19 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Salva`or,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING TO FIX GARBLE IN SLUG</HEAD>
<HEAD>Two Journalists Shot In El Salvador, One Fatally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security forces shot to death a
news photographer and wounded his colleague at a checkpoint near
Ilopango Air Force Base on the eve of El Salvador's presidential
election, officials said Sunday.
   Both men were Salvadoran free-lance photographers who worked
regularly for the Reuters news agency. Representatives of the agency
in San Salvador declined to comment. Armed Forces officials were not
immediately available for comment.
   Justice of the Peace Manuel Jesus de Aguilar said troops who
brought in the body of Roberto Navas, 28, said the shooting occurred
when the two men's motorcycle failed to stop at an air force
checkpoint late Saturday night.
   The magistrate said soldiers radioed the next checkpoint and that
troops there shot the two men when they again refused to stop.
   The armed forces have been on full alert since Tuesday when
leftist guerrillas stepped up their campaign to disrupt Sunday's
election.
   Navas was shot twice, in the back and the side. The judge said he
found at least 22 spent rounds at the scene.
   Luis Galdamez, 34, was shot once in the back and underwent
emergency surgery at Hospital Rosales in San Salvador.
   Dr. Marcelino Caballero told The Associated Press the bullet
entered Galdamez's back and exited through his upper right arm,
injuring a lung. The doctor described the injuries as serious.
   Colleagues said Navas lived near the base, one of the most
strategic military installations in the country, and was on his way
home from work.
   Ilopango is five miles from the capital. The shooting occurred on
the PanAmerican Highway, which runs past the base.
   A nurse at the hospital who asked not to be named told The
Associated Press that an air force ambulance brought Galdamez to the
hospital.
</TEXT>
