<FIRST>r i BC-Salvador 2ndLd-Writethru a0654 03-19 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Salvador, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0654,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>Battle Outside San Salvador On Election Day</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with more details on the fighting and
soundman's death, CORRECTS name of justice of the peace. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers and leftist guerrillas
fought near a power station on the outskirts of the capital early
Sunday, several hours before voting began in the presidential
election.
   Elsewhere, soldiers shot three local journalists at military
checkpoints, killing two of them, officials said.
   Troops from the 1st Infantry Brigade and guerrillas battled near
the power substation in San Ramon, radio reports said. The sounds of
the pre-dawn battle could be heard in downtown San Salvador.
Afterward, military helicopters circled overhead, occasionally
firing rockets at rebel positions.
   No casualty report was immediately available, and it was not
known whether the battle would affect voting in that area.
   The rebels have knocked out much of the electrical power in the
capital and threatened to attack people who drive on the nation's
highways in a bid to disrupt the election, which they are boycotting.
   The Christian Democrat Party of President Jose Napoleon Duarte is
trying to retain power in the election with candidate Fidel Chavez
Mena, a former foreign minister who says he represents new
leadership and dismisses charges of corruption and incompetence.
Duarte by law cannot run for re-election.
   The front-runner, according to the polls, is businessman Alfredo
Cristiani, leader of the rightist and free market Republican
Nationalist Alliance, or Arena. That party, which in the past has
been linked to rightist death squads, already holds a slim edge in
the Salvadoran congress.
   Soldiers reportedly shot and killed a soundman from a local
television crew early Sunday morning in eastern El Salvador.
   Preliminary reports indicated that Mauricio Pineda, 24, died when
soldiers opened fire on the crew's vehicle at a checkpoint near La
Union, acccording to a newsman at Channel 12, William Figueroa.
   The crew was traveling from Morazan province to the coastal city
of La Union, 115 miles from the capital, Figueroa said in a
telephone interview.
   Late Saturday night, soldiers shot to death a news photographer
and wounded his colleague at a checkpoint near Ilopango Air Force
Base, officials said.
   Both men were Salvadoran free-lance photographers who worked
regularly for the Reuters news agency. The agency's San Salvador
office declined to comment.
   Armed forces officials were not immediately available to comment
on either shooting incident.
   Justice of the Peace Manuel de Jesus Aguilar said troops who
brought in the body of photographer Roberto Navas, 28, said the
shooting occurred when the two men's motorcycle failed to stop at an
air force checkpoint.
   The magistrate said soldiers radioed the next checkpoint and that
troops there shot the two men when they again refused to stop.
   Navas was shot twice, in the back and the side. The judge said he
found at least 22 spent rounds at the scene.
   The other photographer, Luis Galdamez, 34, was shot once in the
back and was in serious condition at Hospital Rosales in San
Salvador.
</TEXT>
