<FIRST>r i BC-YeltsinProtest 1stLd-Writethru a0656 03-19 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Yeltsin Protest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0656,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands of Yeltsin Supporters March Through Central Moscow</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with background on party's apparent moves
earlier this month to discredit Yeltsin. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of supporters of maverick communist Boris
N. Yeltsin marched through downtown Moscow Sunday and vowed to hold
a general strike if he does not win election next week to the new
national parliament.
   Yeltsin, who was ousted as Moscow party boss after criticizing
the pace of President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms, claims the
Moscow party machine is working to defeat him. For many Soviets,
Yeltsin epitomizes the quest for more democracy and an end to
special privilege for the government and party elite.
   Chanting ``Yeltsin! Yeltsin!'' at least 3,000 Muscovites set off
from Gorky Park after they were refused permission to hold a
pro-Yeltsin election rally there. They marched to Moscow City Hall
after scores of uniformed police sealed off Kalinin Prospekt leading
to the Kremlin.
   At city hall, the protesters demanded a meeting with Lev N.
Zaikov, the official who replaced Yeltsin as the Soviet capital's
Communist Party boss in November 1987, and who is in charge of the
Moscow party machine they claim is trying to engineer Yeltsin's
defeat.
   A city official armed with a bullhorn clambered on top of a bus
to demand that the crowd disperse, but it remained in front of the
municipal building for more than two hours.
   One pro-Yeltsin speaker perched beside the city hall door called
on the crowd to approve a general strike if Yeltsin does not win the
right to represent Moscow in the March 26 elections for the Congerss
of People's Deputies, and the protesters raised their hands in
agreement. It was not immediately clear when the strike would take
place.
   Earlier this month, the Communist Party released a transcript of
Yeltsin's remarks at a private Central Committee meeting in 1987
that cost him his job as Moscow party boss.
   The transcript said Yeltsin told the gathering that Gorbachev had
become the object of ``intolerable'' glorification. Yeltsin was
named Moscow party chief in December 1985 and a non-voting Politburo
member two months later. He lost both posts as a result of his
remarks at the Oct. 21, 1987 meeting.
   The party said it was publishing a transcript of the meeting in
its new monthly journal, News of the Communist Party Central
Committee, because of requests by workers and party members.
   But a U.S. specialist said the release of 40 pages of scathing
attacks on Yeltsin by Gorbachev and other leaders appeared designed
to hurt the 58-year- old Yeltsin in his bid for political office.
   The transcript showed Yeltsin criticized not only Gorbachev, who
brought him into the Kremlin leadership, but Yegor K. Ligachev, a
conservative force on the ruling Politburo.
</TEXT>
