<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-89 1152EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Spring     03-19 0761</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spring,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spring is Here: The Weather is Changing, So Are The People</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The long, dreary wait for the end of winter is
nearing its end as nature gradually edges into change. Human
patience, also nearing its limits with winter, can draw
encouragement from the spring equinox Monday.
   While the change of seasons is a gradual, often fitful thing,
calendars usually list the solstices and equinoxes as unofficial
markers of these transitions.
   ``The first day of spring is one thing, and the first spring day
is another,'' observed the late Henry Van Dyke, aware that March
weather can be fickle and also that the change of seasons can occur
at markedly different dates in different parts of the nation.
   Even so, millions will welcome spring at 10:28 a.m. EST, the
moment of the vernal equinox, when the sun crosses the equator on
its apparent journey northward, according to astronomers at the U.S.
Naval Observatory in Washington.
   This, and the autumnal equinox in September, are the only two
dates on which the sun rises directly in the east and sets precisely
in the west, the Observatory reports.
   These directions were used to align the Great Pyramids in Egypt
with an error equivalent to the thickness of a piece of string seen
at a distance of six feet, said observatory spokeswoman Gail Cleere.
Ancient graves in Ireland and temples in Guatemala are also aligned
to the equinoxes, she said.
   For the human mind, too, the change may be a point of alignment.
   ``Spring is a transition season when things change very
rapidly,'' observed the late Helmut Landsberg, professor emeritus of
meteorology at the University of Maryland.
   ``One major thing is apparently the change in light ... the most
rapid increase in light intensity occurs between February and
April,'' Landsberg explained, and this seems to affect human glands
and internal reactions.
   Other fluctuations causing humans to react include ``rapid
temperature changes in many places, sometimes highly irregular,
changing from low to high to high to low again,'' said Landsberg,
who researched the biological effects of weather.
   Poets and philosophers have lauded spring over the centuries with
a curious mixture of cheer and woe, reflecting the differing
reactions of humans to the stress of changing weather.
   As Mark Twain observed of New England's weather, ``it gets
through more business in spring than in any other season. I have
counted 136 different kinds of weather inside of 24 hours.''
   This places stress on the body and, scientists are beginning to
believe, the mind also.
   Human responses vary. Malaise, romance and even depression are
among the reactions to these seasonal changes _ although so-called
spring fever has been most widely identified with that vague feeling
of disinterest, mind-wandering and restlessness.
   Nature writer Hal Borland reflected on the seasonal change in the
book ``Twelve Moons of the Year:''
   ``There is something in a mild March day that can touch a man to
the very quick of his being. Just what it is cannot readily be
stated, but it must be compounded of sunlight and air and warmth and
an immeasurable mystery that is partly summed up by the word
`promise.' ''
   ``When the first warm days of spring come, we all feel a desire
to escape, to run away. It becomes difficult to concentrate on
serious matters, and we experience indefinable, vague yearnings that
disturb our psychic balance and have a bad influence on our
professional activities,'' wrote Dr. Michel Gauquelin, a French
psychologist, in his book ``How Atmospheric Conditions Affect Your
Health.''
   ``Spring is a period when new romances start, when fresh plans
are made ... But it is also a season when people experience frequent
changes of mood and have bitter arguments with one another,''
Gauquelin wrote.
   His volume attributes people's response to ``spring hormonal
crisis,'' when the endocrine glands are more active and sexual
interest heightened.
   Whether the changes are the result of hormones, sunlight or other
factors, nearly everyone observes and reacts to them.
   German studies in the 1960s found that most illegitimate
conceptions tended to occur in May which, the researchers suggested,
``seems to indicate that spring may well be the season for all forms
of impulsive behavior.''
   On the darker side, French sociologist Emile Durkheim noted a
half-century ago that suicides increase in the spring.
   The U.S. Centers for Disease Control studied the nation's suicide
rates between 1969 and 1978 and found that during that decade ``the
suicide pattern was distinctly seasonal, above average all spring
and below average all winter.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
