<FIRST>r w AM-CongressRdp     03-19 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress Rdp,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>House To Consider Legislation On Minimum Wage, Protecting Whistleblowers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress is making one of its slowest starts in
recent memory as it heads toward April with little accomplished but
a series of bruising internal battles.
   The Senate will be on a two-week Easter break starting Monday,
but before leaving Friday it confirmed Rep. Dick Cheney as defense
secretary.
   The non-controversial ratification was a breeze after the bitter
struggle over President Bush's first choice for the job, former Sen.
John Tower. The rejection of Tower by a 53-47 vote, largely along
party lines, handed Bush a major defeat and absorbed the Senate for
nearly two months.
   The House, which doesn't start its Easter break until Friday,
faces floor votes this week on raising the minimum wage and
legislation protecting whistleblowers _ government workers who
report corruption within their own agencies.
   House members also may this week get a report from the Ethics
Committee on Speaker Jim Wright. The 12-member committee, which
undertook the inquiry into the Texas Democrat's financial dealings
nine months ago, began deliberating last week on whether Wright
broke House rules.
   Their investigation coupled with the ill-fated fight to raise
congressional pay, and now a search among Republican members for a
minority whip, have sidetracked House action on any major
legislation so far this session.
   House Republicans are expected to choose Wednesday between two
candidates vying for the number two leadership post. Reps. Edward
Madigan of Illinois and Newt Gingrich of Georgia are competing to
succeed Cheney of Wyoming, who resigned last week after being
confirmed as defense secretary.
   Gingrich is the leader of an activist conservative wing of the
party while Madigan, currently the deputy whip, is regarded as a
pragmatist who would probably be more willing to work with the
Democrats to win support for Bush's programs.
   The House is scheduled to vote Tuesday on a bill to expand the
rights of federal employees who blow the whistle on fraud.
   The measure sailed through the Senate last Thursday, 97-0, and
Bush has promised to sign it after the House completes its work.
Similar legislation was the subject of one of President Reagan's
most controversial vetoes.
   The legislation would lower the burden of proof for
whistleblowers who claim they have been punished by their employers
for disclosing misdeeds within their agencies, and increase the
burden of proof for the federal agencies defending their decisions.
   House floor debate over the minimum wage is expected to begin
Wednesday, with Democrats seeking an increase from $3.35 to $4.65 by
1992. Republicans are supporting the Bush proposal that minimum
wages raise only to $4.25 by 1992, with a provision that employers
be allowed to pay new workers $3.35 for the first six months.
   The minimum wage has not increased since 1981.
   Budget negotiators from both the House and Senate are to exchange
offers this week, with Democrats expected to push for military cuts
equal to domestic spending cuts in the fiscal 1990 budget.
   Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif., chairman of the House Budget
Committee, said he and Senate Budget Committee Chairman Jim Sasser,
D-Tenn., planned to work together in drafting a Democratic budget
proposal. In addition to the balance between domestic and military
spending cuts, Panetta said he wants new revenues to equal the
overall spending cuts.
   Also this week, the House banking subcommittee will hold the last
of more than three dozen congressional hearings on the savings and
loan crisis, listening a final time to White House budget director
Richard Darman and Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan before
writing a $100 billion bailout plan.
   Banking committees in both houses, using Bush's proposal as the
foundation but possibly altering many of its key provisions, plan to
put the actual bailout package together the first week Congress is
back in session after Easter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
