<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-89 1233EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Conference     03-19 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Conference,0013</SECOND>
<HEAD>Key Speeches At Advisory Conference Stress Party Line, Unity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major government advisory conference convened
Sunday with speakers urging unity in solving China's growing
economic problems, setting the tone for a legislative session that
opens Monday.
   The brief and businesslike opening session of the 2,081-member
Chinese People's Political Consulative Conference emphasized working
together under the leadership of the ruling Communist Party.
   The somber theme was in sharp contrast to the conference's last
full meeting in April 1988, which saw unprecedented lively debate
and calls for democracy.
   Since then, however, overheated economic growth has produced
chronic shortages, widespread corruption and annual inflation of 36
percent, causing a slowdown in both economic and political reforms.
   Conference Chairman Li Xiannian urged the delegates to share the
government's concerns, offer their suggestions and dedicate
themselves to finding solutions.
   Vice Chairman Qian Weichang, who delivered a 13-page work report,
called on the delegates to ``be ceaselessly diligent'' in pushing
forward the government's economic policies.
   The speeches were greeted with only perfunctory applause by the
delegates who attended the 80-minute session in the Great Hall of
the People in central Beijing.
   The conference draws delegates from among scientists, scholars,
writers and official organizations.
   Its annual plenary session, scheduled to last 10 days, is always
timed to coincide with the annual meeting of the National People's
Congress, China's legislature. The congress begins its 16-day
session Monday.
   Officials reportedly have attempted to discourage unwelcome
debate and criticism of government policies at both meetings this
year because of concern that the economic problems could trigger
social instability.
   Conference official Cheng Siyuan reported that delegates have
made more than 2,000 suggestions to the government since their last
full meeting, and that more than a quarter of these have been
adopted. But he gave no details about the nature of the suggestions.
   He said delegates have been briefed from time to time by
officials on government policy and helped carry it out, especially
by joining in efforts to police prices and cut back on wasteful
construction projects.
   The speakers' clear message was that China's increasingly restive
intellectuals can best serve the country by using their talents to
implement party decisions rather than questioning or criticizing
them.
   The opening session was attended by senior party and government
leaders, including General Secretary Zhao Ziyang, Premier Li Peng
and President Yang Shangkun.
</TEXT>
