<FIRST>r a AM-RinehartProbe     03-19 0960</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rinehart Probe,0987</SECOND>
<HEAD>1978 Sex Abuse Charge Still Follows Popular Columbus, Ohio, Mayor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents of 12th paragraph, `In 1978...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH GRACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The political wounds of a 10-year-old
sexual assault allegation have been reopened for Mayor Dana Rinehart
with a city council probe and filing of a lawsuit that could mean
the end of his hopes of running for governor.
   Rinehart was Franklin County treasurer, a rising star in the
local Republican Party in 1978, when his children's 13-year-old baby
sitter accused him of sexually assaulting her while she slept on a
couch in Rinehart's home. He has denied the allegation and a grand
jury failed to indict him.
   But a newspaper story last fall resulted in the council
investigation and one by the police department into whether a police
officer spied on the girl's family in 1983 in an attempt to
discredit her and gain a police endorsement for Rinehart, who was
running for mayor.
   Rinehart didn't get the endorsement, but he won the election. He
is now serving his second four-year term as mayor of Ohio's capital
city.
   Rinehart, 43, said he does not know how the resurrection of what
has become known locally as ``the baby sitter incident'' will affect
his political future, which he at one time had hoped would be spent
in the governor's office.
   Once-plentiful rumors that Rinehart planned to run for governor
in 1990 have died down since the investigations, despite an Ohio
State University poll in January that showed he had a 78 percent
approval rating in the city of approximately 600,000. It was his
highest rating ever.
   ``Part of me would love to (be governor), but part of me says no.
I've had a taste of politics that has not been good. The jury is
still out in my heart and in my head,'' he said.
   The former baby sitter, Vicki Rae Pardue, now 23, said she hopes
Rinehart's political future is indeed wounded.
   ``I don't think Rinehart has any business being anywhere in
politics, which includes governor,'' she said at a news conference
on Wednesday.
   On Thursday _ two weeks after the council hearings _ Ms. Pardue's
stepmother, Linda Pardue, filed suit in U.S. District Court against
Rinehart and the police officer accused of spying, contending they
engaged in a political conspiracy against the family.
   In 1978, Ms. Pardue told police that she was asleep on Rinehart's
couch when she awoke to find him performing oral sex on her. She
contended he then kissed her on the mouth, said he would be back
later and walked out of the room.
   Ms. Pardue later passed a police-administered polygraph test.
Rinehart, who was advised by his lawyer not to submit to a police
test, said he passed a privately administered polygraph test.
   For 10 years, questions have surrounded the propriety of a
Franklin County grand jury hearing into Ms. Pardue's allegations.
Rinehart was allowed to testify before the grand jury _ an
opportunity that is only rarely afforded the accused in Ohio.
   Also permitted to testify on Rinehart's behalf was a psychiatric
expert who told the jury that, although he had not interviewed Ms.
Pardue, she may have dreamed the incident and believed it had
actually happened.
   The grand jury declined to indict Rinehart.
   The ``baby sitter incident'' resurfaced last October when The
Plain Dealer in Cleveland reported that police officer John Morgan,
a devoted Rinehart supporter, had conducted secret, politically
motivated surveillance on the Pardue family for two months in 1983.
   After Rinehart was elected, Morgan was promoted from the police
force to deputy city safety director and then deputy city
development director. He was fired after he refused to cooperate in
a police investigation a few days after the Plain Dealer story.
   Rinehart says he knew nothing about Morgan's investigation or the
officer's 13-page report of his findings until the newspaper queried
Morgan about it Oct. 7. He plays down the controversy surrounding
Morgan's activities.
   ``We've had city employees who, unfortunately, have done things
that are out of line. We've had worse stuff than this. We had a
police officer who robbed banks,'' Rinehart said.
   The internal police investigation of Morgan, which ended in
November, found no criminal activity, although police said their
investigation was hampered by the fact that Morgan refused to be
interviewed.
   The findings of a council investigation _ which concluded March 2
after three days of testimony from Rinehart, Morgan and others _
will be known next month.
   Testimony at the hearings raised questions about whether Rinehart
knew of the report and who in the police department and his campaign
may have authorized the surveillance.
   Morgan, who testified under a grant of immunity, said he
conducted the surveillance with neither the knowledge nor permission
of his superiors, Rinehart, or any member of the Rinehart campaign.
   ``I didn't feel they had a need to know,'' Morgan said.
   He testified that he researched the Pardue family's geneological
history, recorded license numbers of mourners at the funeral of Miss
Pardue's father in 1983, and obtained information on the family's
banking records without obtaining a subpoena _ an order required
under federal bank right-to-privacy laws. Morgan said he conducted
the investigation on city time and used city equipment.
   Rinehart's testimony that he didn't know about Morgan's report
until last fall was contradicted by testimony from two local
reporters, who told the City Council they had confronted Rinehart
with a copy of it in 1983. A third said he'd seen a copy of the
report in 1983.
   The Pardue lawsuit seeks unspecified compensatory and punitive
damages as well as preliminary and permanent injunctions ordering
the defendants to halt any further investigation of the family. No
hearing date was set.
</TEXT>
