<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-Violence     03-19 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Violence,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Policemen Wounded in Grenade Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four black policemen were
wounded when a hand grenade was hurled through the gates of a police
training center in Soweto, police said Sunday.
   No arrests were reported, and no one claimed responsibility for
the Saturday night attack. Police have blamed similar past attacks
on the outlawed African National Congress guerrilla movement.
   Police said 19 black youths were arrested after attackers
firebombed a government building in a black township near the port
city of Durban, also Saturday night. Officers fired tear gas,
shotguns and pistols to disperse the bombers, and one youth was
wounded, police headquarters said.
   In Soweto, the main black township outside Johannesburg, a mob
caught a suspected rapist, and stoned and burned the man to death
Saturday. Police confirmed the killing, and two newspapers published
photographs of the burning body.
   In another development, anti-apartheid groups announced prayer
services nationwide on Tuesday in support of detainees, particularly
those staging hunger strikes to protest being held without charge.
They are held under provisions of a state of emergency in effect
since 1986.
   Tuesday will be the 29th anniversary of the Sharpeville Massacre,
in which police shot and killed 69 unarmed blacks protesting South
Africa's policies of racial separation.
   Two hunger strikers are reported in critical condition. Lawyers
and activists say Sandile Thusi, held in Durban, has not eaten for
31 days, and Donsie Khumalo, a union leader held in Pretoria, has
refused both food and liquids for 10 days.
</TEXT>
