<FIRST>r i AM-Tibet     03-19 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tibet,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0688 to fix garble in keyword.</HEAD>
<HEAD>China Condemns U.S., European Resolutions on Tibet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China condemned as ``interference'' separate
resolutions by the U.S. Senate and European Parliament accusing
Beijing of human rights violations in Tibet, official reports said
Sunday.
   ``We express strong indignation and deep regret,'' the People's
Daily said, quoting a harshly-worded statement from the Foreign
Affairs Committee of the National People's Congress.
   The legislative committee also lodged ``a strong protest'' Sunday
against the U.S. resolution, the Xinhua News Agency said. Similar
resolutions in the past have become major points of friction between
the two countries.
   The U.S. resolution ``blatantly supports a handful of separatists
in Tibet,'' Xinhua quoted the statement as saying.
   The committee Saturday condemned the European Parliament
resolution, which urged Beijing to lift martial law and called on
European nations to help mediae the Tibetan problem.
   ``The Tibetan people are a member of the big family of the
Chinese nation. Any attempt to internationalize the Tibetan question
on the excuse of human rights is firmly opposed by the Chinese
government and will never succeed,'' the statement said.
   Its strong language is in keeping with China's policy of harshly
rejecting outside criticism of its actions in Tibet, which it claims
has been part of China's territory since the 13th century.
   Many Tibetans say they enjoyed de facto independence before
Chinese communist troops entered in 1950. They accuse the Chinese of
human rights violations and of trying to destroy Tibet's
Buddhist-based culture.
   The European Parliament passed its resolution Thursday about the
martial law China imposed March 8 after three days of anti-Chinese
violence in the Tibetan capital, Lhasa. At least 12 people were
killed in the fourth bloody Tibetan-Chinese confrontation in the
past 18 months.
   The Parliament also appealed to foreign ministers of the
12-member European Community to offer their mediation.
   ``We are firmly opposed to and will by no means accept'' such
mediation, the Chinese statement said. ``No foreign government,
organization or individual is allowed to meddle in the question of
negotiations between the Chinese central government and the Dalai
Lama.'' The Dalai Lama is a self-exile many Tibetans consider their
temporal and spiritual leader.
   The U.S. Senate, which also acted Thursday, has approved
non-binding resolutions in the past urging the State Department to
pressure China to end alleged human rights violations in Tibet.
   Two days after China imposed martial law on Tibet, the U.S. State
Department issued a statement of concern, which China dismissed as
interference.
   ``The Chinese government is entirely justified and above reproach
in taking the necessary measures to uphold law and maintain order,''
the Chinese legislative committee said.
   It reiterated China's willingness to hold talks with the Dalai
Lama, but ruled out independence or autonomy for the remote region.
   ``We strongly demand that the European parliament immediately
stop its interference in China's internal affairs so as to prevent
doing any harm to our bilateral relations,'' it said.
   It similarly warned the U.S. Senate to act in the ``interests of
safeguarding Chinese-U.S. relations.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
