<HEAD>Dissidents Call For President's Ouster, Removal of U.S. Troops</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SEL1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of students and workers
cheered calls Sunday by dissident leaders for the ouster of
President Roh Tae-woo and the immediate withdrawal of U.S. troops
from South Korea.
   Leaders of the United National Democratic Movement, the main
dissident alliance, told a rally of 5,000 people at Hanyang
University that opposition forces must unite to defeat the
government in a pending national referendum.
   ``Down with Roh Tae-woo!'' and ``Yankee go home!'' protesters
chanted.
   Some students hurled firebombs and rocks at riot police in a
brief clash after the rally. Police fired volleys of tear gas that
drove protesters back.
   Thousands of riot police had surrounded the school, but there was
little trouble after alliance leaders urged people to disperse
peacefully.
   Police officials reported no arrests or injuries.
   Alliance chairman Lee Bu-yong told the rally Roh was a front for
military rule.
   ``We cannot suffer any more under the Roh regime. We must oust
the Roh regime without fail,'' Lee said.
   Paik Ki-wan, another leading dissident, denounced the United
States for supporting the Roh government and charged Washington was
trying to control South Korea like a colony.
   ``The real culprit is the United States,'' he said.
   Protesters repeatedly called for the withdrawal of 42,000 U.S.
troops based in South Korea. The United States has said they will
remain as long as the South Korean government wants them.
   Roh, a former general who won a presidential election in December
1987, is expected this week to announce plans for a national
referendum on his performance as president.
   The government says Roh will not step down if he is defeated.
Some opposition groups are demanding he resign if defeated.
</TEXT>
