<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-Monarchy     03-19 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Monarchy,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Son of Last King Recognizes Republic, Wants to Return</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The son of Italy's last king for the first time
recognized the republic, renewing a campaign for him and his son to
be allowed to return from a 43-year exile despite a constitutional
ban, media reports said Sunday.
   In a letter to Italian president Francisco Cossiga published in
Italian newspapers, Victor Emmanuel wrote from exile in Switzerland
that he is not, however, renouncing his claim to the former throne
of the House of Savoy.
   Victor Emmanuel, 51, wrote the letter Saturday, the sixth
anniversary of the death of his father, King Umberto II.
   ``I want to do today what my father was not in a position to do,
and that is to recognize this incontrovertible reality that is the
Italian republic,'' he wrote.
   He said he was appealing especially on behalf of his 17-year-old
son, Emmanuel Filiberto, whom he hoped would be allowed to attend an
Italian military academy and university.
   The letter sparked immediate speculation that Victor Emmanuel was
relinquishing his claim to the throne, but he quickly denied that
was the case.
   ``I want to return to Italy as soon as possible,'' he told
Milan's Corriere Della Sera newspaper. ``I say simply that I
recognize the republic because it's there. I will never, never
renounce my royal prerogatives. I am totally monarchist.''
   Victor Emmanuel has appealed in the past for the government to
allow his family to return. Italy's 1947 constitution, however, bans
the entry of Victor Emmanuel and his heirs from the country and
would need a two-thirds majority in both houses of Parliament to be
altered.
   Umberto II reigned for 26 days before being forced into exile in
1946, when Italians voted by a slim margin to abolish the monarchy.
Umberto II died in Geneva in 1983 at the age of 78.
   In 1987, the government lifted the constitutional ban on the
entry of his widow, the ex-queen Maria Jose. She has since returned
to Italy on a few occasions, but continues to live in Switzerland.
   The House of Savoy ruled Piedmont for nine centuries and its
kings reigned in Italy from 1861 to 1946.
</TEXT>
