<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-89 1408EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-EasternEx-POW Bjt   03-19 0788</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern Ex-POW, Bjt,0808</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilots Who Saw Combat Don't Think Lorenzo's So Tough</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot laughed when asked why he is willing to
risk his job in the showdown between Eastern Airlines and its unions.
   ``For five years, every time the little guy with the rifle walked
by, he made me bow down,'' said Jerry Gerndt. ``I came out of
Vietnam with my head held up, and I'm not going to spend the rest of
my life looking down when I pass other pilots.''
   He is among the 3,400 Eastern pilots who stunned management by
joining the March 4 walkout by the Machinists union. He's also a
former prisoner of war.
   Air Force 1st Lt. Gerald L. Gerndt, piloting an F-4 Phantom
fighter on a bombing mission to Hanoi, was shot down Aug. 23, 1967.
Five years and five months later, Gerndt was flown out of Hanoi on a
U.S. transport plane.
   He carried with him the wounds of years of torture and
mistreatment that led to broken ribs, damaged joints, hepatitis and
repeated bouts with dysentery. He also carried out a changed
philosophy of life.
   ``Little things in life don't bother you so much,'' said Gerndt,
46. ``You want to stand up and be counted if someone is trying to
take advantage of people and trying to force his ideas and views on
them.''
   Eastern, which had hoped to keep at least 25 percent of its
pre-strike schedule of 1,040 daily flights during the strike, is
struggling to maintain 10 percent, with the walkout well into its
third week.
   The executives put in place three years ago by Texas Air Corp.
Chairman Frank Lorenzo admitted they badly overestimated the number
of pilots who would keep flying. Only about 200 Eastern pilots have
crossed the picket lines.
   Pilots often have ignored the picket lines of other airline
unions, but the Eastern pilots say they learned from Continental
pilots, who lost their union along with the Machinsts in 1983 even
though the pilots didn't honor picket lines.
   The pilots also say they believe that Lorenzo, whose Texas Air
also owns Continental, is bent on stripping Eastern of its assets
while chipping away at employees' pay and work conditions.
   Pilots union spokesman J.B. Stokes said another key to
understanding the Eastern pilots' resolve is that 75 percent or more
are military veterans, many with Vietnam experience.
   ``One of the problems is this management has been trying to use
intimidation and coercion,'' said Stokes, a B-52 pilot who flew
Vietnam combat missions in 1969. ``It speaks to the Frank Lorenzo
philosophy and shows how badly he misunderstands these pilots.
   ``These people know what it really is to be afraid; they've put
their lives on the line in a hostile environment,'' Stokes said.
``If I survived Vietnam, I damn sure am not going to be concerned
about a guy putting memos on a bulletin board.''
   Gerndt said as much as he loves flying and the lifestyle of a
pilot for a major carrier, the job's not worth giving in to
``demeaning management.''
   He recounted his Vietnam experience last week, talking by
telephone from his Milwaukee financial consulting office where he
works when not walking picket lines.
   He was in one of the first bombing missions into North Vietnam
when he was shot down. Gerndt and his co-pilot ejected about 20
miles north of Hanoi and he could hear bullets pinging the
parachute's canopy as he fell.
   They were captured when they landed, stripped of their clothes
and marched to Hanoi. Most of his imprisonment was in the infamous
``Hanoi Hilton.''
   ``It started as soon as I got there. It was just like everything
you ever heard about: beatings, `rope tricks' where they tie you up
and put stress on different joints, like a variation of the rack.
   ``At times you wonder if you will die there. But you have to have
hope. That's all you have left,'' Gerndt said.
   He was freed in January 1973 as U.S. involvement in Vietnam was
winding down, and by that August, he was flying for Eastern. Shortly
afterward he was laid off because of cutbacks because of the energy
crisis, and he got an MBA from Stanford University.
   Gerndt said his Eastern salary is below the $70,000 to $75,000
average the Air Line Pilots Association estimates Eastern pilots
earn annually. He said given the education and skills the pilots
have, they resent Lorenzo and other managers' efforts to put them
``near the bottom of the barrel'' in the industry.
   ``Basically, I look at it that he's trying to destroy
(employees') way of living,'' Gerndt said. ``Why would I want to
work for a man like that?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
