<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-89 1440EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Lucas     03-19 0676</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lucas,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Civil Rights Groups Express Unease, Rather Than Opposition to Appointment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citing William Lucas' lack of experience, civil
rights groups are expressing concern that he might be the wrong
choice to head the Justice Department's civil rights division.
   Civil rights leaders have not taken a formal position on William
Lucas, who Attorney General Dick Thornburgh has designated as his
choice to head the department's civil rights division.
   But these leaders say they are continuing to study Lucas' record
to determine what position they will ultimately take if President
Bush nominates the black Republican from Michigan as assistant
attorney general for civil rights.
   ``So far we are still quite concerned about the nomination
because the position is extremely important for the civil rights
community,'' said Julius Chambers, director of the NAACP Legal
Defense and Education Fund, Inc.
   Lucas, 61, is ``a person who hasn't really been involved in civil
rights litigation for more than 20 years and a person who has taken
some positions, for whatever reason, in civil rights that show no
sensitivity for the problems,'' said Chambers.
   Chambers notes Lucas' opposition to affirmative action, saying
positions he has taken on school desegregation ``were quite
bothersome.''
   Besides Lucas' lack of experience, Washington attorney William
Taylor said he is concerned about Lucas' record as sheriff in the
Detroit area.
   The record includes a court finding that he was legally
responsible for injuries suffered by a prisoner who was beaten while
in the custody of Wayne County sheriffs' deputies.
   The 1976 beating of Salvatore Marchese by an unidentified person
who was admitted to his locked holding cell at a suburban Detroit
station was the subject of a strongly-worded 1985 ruling by the 6th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   The court cited Lucas' ``failure to provide a trained and
disciplined county law enforcement agency'' or to investigate the
beating incident.
   Lucas had testified that he did not know about the incident and
therefore would not have been able to investigate it.
   But the appellate court said he was still legally liable because
``in his official capacity he had a duty to both know and act.''
   ``The sheriff's subsequent failure to order and direct an
investigation which disclosed exactly who were the perpetrators of
these brutal violations of the U.S. Constitution and to administer
censure and punishment served to confirm the existence of an
unstated `policy' of toleration of illegal brutality toward any
county prisoner who had threatened the life of a sheriff's deputy,''
the court said.
   ``I was sheriff an awful long time,'' Lucas said. ``There were
many cases that required investigation. This is one case, that is
one too many of course, but this was a very turbulent time.''
   Lucas was sheriff from 1969 to 1982, when he was elected county
executive. After switching to the Republican Party, Lucas made an
unsuccessful run for Michigan governor in 1986.
   He now wants to head a Justice Department division that both
civil and criminal civil rights laws, including statutes barring
police from violating constitutional rights of criminal suspects.
The division has brought many prosecutions for systematic police
brutality against blacks.
   During his tenure as sheriff, Lucas said, ``We had a reputation
for taking strong actions against anyone who violated department
rules and particularly civil rights.''
   Asked if he had ever fired deputies for brutality, Lucas said:
``I am certain that we did. Deputies were fired for all sorts of
violations.
   ``I have never been accused of being insensitive of the rights of
anyone,'' said Lucas, a former policeman and FBI agent who worked as
Justice Department civil rights investigator in the 1960s.
   Deborah Gordon, the lawyer who represented Marchese in the civil
case, said she never challenged Lucas' statements that he didn't
know about the Marchese beating.
   Although she doesn't personally hold Lucas responsible for the
beating she said: ``Could the department have been run better?
Probably. What it indicated to me was a complete lack of concern of
any kind on the part of the department about this.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
