<FIRST>u i AM-Philippines     03-19 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Killing of Congressman Underscores Cult of Political Violence</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The assassination of a congressman
shows the cult of political violence still haunts the Philippines,
despite President Corazon Aquino's vow to end ``rule by the bullet.''
   Rep. Moises Espinosa, 55, a member of a pro-Aquino party, was
shot to death Friday with two other people after arriving in the
airport in his home province, Masbate, after a flight from Manila
240 miles away.
   No arrests have been reported. But Manila newspapers quoted
relatives as speculating that Espinosa, from an influential
political family, was slain by business or political rivals.
   He was the first congressman slain since Mrs. Aquino came to
power in 1986 after a civilian-military uprising toppled President
Ferdinand Marcos. He was vice chairman of the public order and
security committee in the House of Representatives.
   ``This is something we in public life have to expect in our job,
especially in the kind of politics we still have,'' said House
Speaker Ramon Mitra after the Espinosa killing.
   Mitra was critically injured 16 years ago during a bombing at a
political rally in Manila.
   During a speech in Japan in November 1986, Mrs. Aquino boasted
that her ``people power'' administration had replaced ``rule by the
bullet with rule by the ballot.''
   However, Espinosa is the latest in a lengthening list of
politicians, journalists, human rights lawyers, municipal officials,
and labor leaders slain in unsolved political killings during the
Aquino administration.
   The victims include Local Governments Secretary Jaime Ferrer, who
was gunned down near his home in August 1987. Ferrer became the
first Philippine Cabinet member slain while in office.
   Others are labor leader Rolando Olalia, kidnapped and murdered in
November 1986; leftist leader Lean Alejandro, slain in September
1987; and Vicente Gerochi, a senior official of the Commission on
Elections, who was ambushed near his home last month.
   More than 90 people, including about 40 candidates, were killed
in political violence during the campaign for January 1988 regional
elections.
   About 50 people died in campaign violence before May 1987
congressional balloting.
   The military says such violence was worse during the Marcos
years, and it often blames killings on Communist rebels. Indeed, the
rebels have claimed responsibility for killing hundreds of police,
soldiers and low-level officials in the last three years.
   But many Filipinos believe most killings of politicians have been
the work of political rivals.
   ``If there is an outstanding truism about Filipino political
life, it is this: Politically motivated murder is not meant to be
punished,'' said the independent Philippine Daily Globe. ``In fact,
what exists are the trappings of government without its essence. We
have laws that are all too frequently _ and with total impunity _
violated.''
   Killings of political figures, which grab headlines, also seem to
go hand-in-hand with a general lawlessness that the government has
been unable to contain. Last year, about 3,700 killings were
reported in greater Manila, which has a population of about 8
million.
   The Committee to Protect Journalists reported in Washington last
week that of 26 journalists killed last year in the line of duty,
five were in the Philippines.
   Most of the Filipino journalists slain last year had reported on
illegal gambling and other corruption in the provinces.
   By comparison, war-ravaged Afghanistan registered four killings
of journalists in 1988.
</TEXT>
