<FIRST>r a AM-Detroit-Homeless     03-19 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Detroit-Homeless,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homeless Unimpressed By City's `Warming Center' Ordinance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Outside Homeless, which subs for AM-DC-Homeless on AM-News
Advisory.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KOLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newspapers frequently detail the plight of the
nation's homeless. Aldo White doesn't read the papers _ he sleeps in
them on Third Street.
   White, hardened by years of begging, either is mute or chooses
not to speak. He communicates with fierce brown eyes and with the
cane that props him up on his only leg.
   One tap means ``no;'' two taps mean ``yes.'' When White is asked
whether he will benefit from a city ordinance ordering the opening
of a vacant building to the homeless, he stares down at his stub and
taps once.
   White is one of the thousands of homeless who wander the streets
of the nation's sixth-largest city as officials try to find them
shelter. Their challenge: providing it without jeopardizing
Detroit's economic rebirth.
   The relationship between advocates for the homeless and Mayor
Coleman A. Young frequently has been stormy. Both sides disagree on
the numbers of the city's shelterless.
   Advocates insist there are 10,000 to 60,000 others like White, a
statistic disputed by Robert Berg, Young's press secretary.
   ``That's absurd,'' he said. ``If you go out and check the
shelters, you'll see that most of them are half empty. There's not a
single case this winter of somebody not having a place to spend the
night.''
   The ordinance that went into effect March 10, requiring Young to
designate a vacant public building or rent a private one as a
``warming center,'' is a scaled-down version of a measure that would
have opened 39 downtown buildings to the homeless.
   Young vetoed the more expansive plan, saying it would cost $2
million and threaten Detroit's convention business. The City
Council, which proposed the ordinance, fell short in an attempt to
override the veto.
   The warming center opened last week in a recreation building on
the city's east side. No homeless showed up because word hadn't yet
spread on the streets, the shelter's operators said.
   Meanwhile, community leaders speculated about the impact of
Young's veto on his widely expected run this fall for a fifth
four-year term.
   Theresa Smith, spokeswoman for the Detroit-Wayne County Union of
the Homeless, said her group is urging the homeless it aids to
register to vote.
   Smith knows the anguish of homelessness. A year ago, her landlord
evicted her and her five children after the family couldn't afford
to pay its gas bill.
   ``I went from shelter to shelter,'' she said. ``My family called
me the Shelter Queen. When the mayor says (the original ordinance)
would have cost $2 million, he's admitting there's a terrible,
desperate need.''
   Last week _ while the City Council debated the merits of its
housing plan _ C. Patrick Babcock, who heads the state's welfare
agency, urged officials to set aside part of the $500 million spent
annually on temporary housing in Michigan and invest it in a more
permanent solution.
   Paul Hubbard, director of New Detroit, a coalition aimed at
improving the quality of life in the city, agrees.
   ``Putting the homeless in public buildings doesn't solve the
problem,'' he said. ``Ten years ago, homeless were derelicts with
Army jackets and wine bottles hanging out of their pockets. Now,
they're women and children.
   ``You need permanent public housing. Otherwise, as soon as it's
warm, they're back on the streets again.''
   Young's veto of the original homeless plan probably won't
backfire on him politically because it was replaced by the modified
measure, Hubbard said. ``The mayor sees the need and he's done
something about it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
