<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon-Israel     03-19 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Israel,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israelis And Pro-Iranian Shiites Clash; 6 Wounded</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RASHAYA, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops and allied Lebanese
militiamen traded artillery fire with pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem
guerrillas in south Lebanon on Sunday, and police said six people
were wounded.
   They said the brief exchange flared after a 75-strong armored
Israeli force and fighters of the Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army
entered the village of Dallafeh village, just outside Israel's
self-designated security zone, in search of pro-Iranian guerrillas.
   ``They destroyed two houses in the village, but they didn't find
any guerrillas,'' said a police spokesman, who by custom is not
named. ``As they were pulling out after a four-hour search they came
under fire from guerrillas of the Islamic Resistance.''
   Israeli and Lebanese troops retaliated by shelling the villages
of Dallaya and Yohmor, two miles north of the security zone.
   Three Shiite civilians and three Lebanese militiamen were
wounded, police reported.
   Islamic Resistance is Shiite fundamentalists sponsored by the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God.
   Israel established the six- to 10-mile wide security zone in 1985
when it withdrew the bulk of its army from south Lebanon after a
three-year occupation.
</TEXT>
