<FIRST>r a AM-ShipwreckSearch     03-19 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shipwreck Search,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>Explorer Plans to Plumb Boston Harbor for 18th-Century Shipwreck</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Jonathan Blasczak was 12 years old, he read
about an 18th-century French ship that sank in Boston Harbor. Twenty
years later, he has received permission to search for the wreck and
its reputed riches.
   After researching the journals of French soldiers and other
documents, Blasczak, 32, a construction worker from Hopkinton,
believes the ship contains between $50 million and $500 million in
gold coins and other cargo.
   ``It's like reliving a childhood dream,'' said Blasczak, who read
about the Magnifique in an Edward Rowe Snow book, `Shipwrecks Around
New England.' ``Back then, it might not have been that easy to do
but with the technology we have now, it's possible.''
   Last fall, the state Board of Underwater Archaelogical Resources
approved Blasczak's request to search for the Magnifique, a French
vessel that ran aground near the end of the Revolutionary War.
   Blasczak plans to begin initial work on the site within a few
days.
   The 218-foot ship may have been carrying up to 500 soldiers when
it sank in August 1782, said Blasczak. The wooden vessel was
weakened by a tour of the Caribbean where a parasite called the
teredo had eaten away at its hull.
   Blasczak said his research could not uncover whether men died
when the ship sank in less than an hour or if they were ferried to
safety.
   ``The French were very secretive about their navy back then,'' he
said.
   Blasczak said records culled form the Marine Museum in Paris and
the Journals of French soldiers allude to a cargo that may have
included 300,000 pistoles _ French gold coins that were also called
Louis d'Ors.
   Last year, Blasczak and his team dove with a magnetometer, which
detects magnetic metals, and a sonar system, which uses sound waves
to detect objects, and found a large mass they believe to be the
wreck.
   They believe the ship is under 20 feet of water and buried under
5 feet of sand and mud. Blasczak said the currents have changed over
the years and the mud is now washing off the Magnifique, exposing it.
   Victor Mastone, associate director of the state Board of
Underwater Archaelogical Resources, said Blasczak's plan is the
second one involving a search in Boston Harbor, the nation's
filthiest harbor.
   Barry Clifford, who found the wreck of the Whydah off the
Massachusetts coast several years ago with artifacts estimated at
$40 million, has received initial permission to search for the
crates of tea thrown into the harbor during the Boston Tea Party
before the Revolutionary War.
   ``It's like people are just finding out there's a lot out
there,'' said Mastone.
   Blasczak is working with a crew of seven, including three divers.
Robert Cembrola, executive director of the Marine Museum of Fall
River, is in charge of cataloging any items retrieved from the wreck.
   ``I called my best friend from 20 years ago and told him about
it,'' said Blasczak. ``He couldn't believe I was actually doing what
we talked about so long ago.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
