<FIRST>r a AM-BotchedFuneral     03-19 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Botched Funeral,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Family Of Woman Files $1 Million Lawsuit Claiming Botched Funeral</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A family has sued a cemetery for $1
million, claiming that a damaged casket allowed mourners to see the
deceased's foot and a cemetery employee interrupted the funeral to
demand that the rabbi move his car.
   All of this happened at the funeral of Pauline Rosenthal last
year, family members said in a lawsuit filed in Broward County
Circuit Court last week.
   Her husband, Arthur Rosenthal, and her two daughters and their
families are seeking the damages from Menorah Gardens and Funeral
Chapels for putting them through an emotional wringer at the funeral
in January 1988.
   Menorah Gardens funeral director Mark Weissman said through a
spokesperson that he knew nothing about the lawsuit.
   ``It was a terible, terrible thing,'' said Mrs. Rosenthal's
daughter, Linda Zimmerman of Northbrook, Ill. ``We are looking
forward to our day in court.''
   Mrs. Zimmerman and other relatives declined to discuss details of
the case on the advice of their attorney.
   The lawsuit said the grave site was ``prepared in a sloppy and
unkempt manner'' and chairs were filthy and rusty, and the
scaffolding was uneven and covered with artificial carpet.''
   This caused mourners to ``trip and stumble,'' the lawsuit said.
   Pallbearers were supposed to carry the casket from a hearse to
the grave site. Instead, ``slovenly attired and unclean'' cemetery
workers did so until family members insisted on completing the task
themselves.
   During the service, a cemetery worker demanded that the rabbi
move his car from a designated parking area, the lawsuit said.
   When the rabbi continued with the service, the employee wrapped a
chain around the bumper of the rabbi's car and ``a backhoe or other
piece of heavy equipment backed within close range of the
automobile.''
   As the casket was being lowered, it slipped as it was being
placed in a vault. Two lids popped open, exposing the deceased
woman's foot with a white tag attached to it, the lawsuit said.
   The casket would not fit in the vault and the straps supporting
the casket could not be removed without more jarring of the casket
and prying it with iron bars, it said.
   In June, Arthur Rosenthal ordered a tombstone and specified that,
for religious reasons, it should not be placed atop his wife's grave
until Nov. 18. He and one of his daughters asked to see Mrs.
Rosenthal's grave but were told that the original marker had been
chewed up by a lawn mower, according to the lawsuit.
   In September, Rosenthal visited his wife's grave and found that
her headstone was on it, contrary to his wishes.
</TEXT>
