<FIRST>r i AM-France-Elections     03-19 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Elections,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Left Makes Gains In Municipal Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Francois Mitterand's governing Socialists
emerged the big winners Sunday in the second round of municipal
elections, winning control of several large cities from the
conservative and center-right parties.
   Early results showed such conservative bastions as Strasbourg,
Mulhouse, Brest, Dunkirk, Orleans, Blois, Avignon and Quimper
falling into Socialist hands.
   Frequently city elections have been used to criticize the
national government, but this year results seemed to confirm the
leftist trend that re-elected Mitterrand last spring and gave him a
leftist majority in the National Assembly.
   ``It is the first time that we have seen a government receive a
powerful, popular encouragement during the municipal elections,''
said Interior Minister Pierre Joxe, a Socialist.
   The second round was required in 832 towns and cities larger than
3,500 where no candidates won more than 50 percent of the vote in
last Sunday's first round.
   Turnout in the ninth election in less than a year was estimated
at between 72 and 73.5 percent.
   A national projection by the TF1 television network showed the
Socialist Party and its allies winning 78 cities with populations
above 30,000, compared to 66 in 1983 municipal elections.
   The Communist Party won mayoral seats in 48 cities, compared to
53 six years ago; the conservative Rally for the Republic won 45 big
cities compared to 47 in 1983; and the center-right Union for French
Democracy won 39 cities as opposed to 41 six years ago.
   The right was losing few municipalities of more than 30,000, but
they were behind in important cities and taking only smaller, less
important ones from the left.
   There was some good news on the right, however. Michel Noir, a
conservative deputy in the National Assembly, defeated a
center-right incumbent in Lyon, France's third-largest city.
   Former President Valery Giscard d'Estaing, now head of the
center-right Union for French Democracy, said the municipal
elections were less ideological than in the past.
   ``The Socialists registered a certain progress,'' he said. ``In
all, France is still divided in two'' between right and left.
</TEXT>
