<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-89 1716EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PhotoFraud     03-19 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Photo Fraud,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Owners Sought for 5,500 Baby Photos</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bright-eyed innocent-looking babies peer out of
nearly 5,500 photos seized in a fraud investigation. But these kids
are no criminals; their mugs come from two bankrupt photo companies
that collected money for the pictures and didn't deliver.
   Staff members of the Cook County state's attorney's office are
trying to track down parents to deliver the goods. The photos come
from the Sheridan-Peter Pan Studios and American Color Portraits,
both of Chicago, and the companies' photo subcontractors.
   Three years ago, the photo companies declared bankruptcy _ after
collecting money for the photographs, but before delivering them to
waiting parents.
   Most customers were from the Chicago area, but some came from
Indiana, Michigan and Wisconsin, officials said.
   ``It was more than a normal business failure,'' said Allen
Reiffman, supervisor of the prosecutor's consumer fraud unit. ``They
knew they were going out of business. They still signed people and
took their money and their memories.''
   The consumer fraud unit took possession of the photographs last
year after suing the companies, accusing them of fraud.
   ``Now, the only problem is that many parents have moved,'' said
Neomi Hernandez, a state's attorney paralegal. ``We have no way of
tracking them.''
   It took Ms. Hernandez 100 telephone calls to locate three parents
who were still at their present addresses.
   One successful call linked Adam Manring, 4, of Elgin, with his
photo when he was 2.
   ``I knew something was wrong when six months passed without our
getting the photos,'' said his mother, Vicki Manring. ``Then the
studio's phone was disconnected.''
   Gloria Saffold McCall had another story. She had planned as a
gift for her aging mother a family portrait of Ms. McCall's 12
brothers and sisters and her mother's 50 grandchildren and
great-grandchildren.
   It took months to get everyone together.
   ``Peter Pan shot the picture in my house,'' said Ms. McCall. ``We
had to reshoot it again. It was still all wrong.''
   Finally, she said, she had 13 separate family portraits taken for
$1,500. But she never got the pictures.
   Last Thursday, she received one sister's portrait. The rest are
still missing.
</TEXT>
