<DOCNO> AP890319-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-89 1722EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina     03-19 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>Principal, Interest `Unpayable,' Central Bank President Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Argentina's foreign debt is
unpayable and the country won't reduce the amount it owes until
after the national election in May, the Central Bank president was
quoted as saying Sunday.
   ``We made a payment of $270 million during the last four months
of 1988,'' Jose Luis Machinea said in an interview published by the
newspaper Pagina 12.
   ``After the election, whoever is voted in will have to discuss a
strategy'' with creditor banks, he said.
   Argentina's $59 billion debt is third-highest among developing
countries. Payments on principal have been deferred, but interest
bills are expected to reach $6 billion this year.
   The country currently owes $2.5 billion in overdue payments to
private banks, Machinea was quoted as saying. The Central Bank
rarely discloses the level of foreign reserves, but banking sources
put them at about $2 billion.
   ``The debt is absolutely unpayable, both the interest and the
capital,'' Machinea was quoted as saying.
</TEXT>
