<DOCNO> AP890319-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-89 1722EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-France-Chemicals     03-19 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Chemicals,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Search Suspended For Chemicals in English Channel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHERBOURG, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High winds and heavy seas forced workers
to suspend their search Sunday for containers of insecticide and
other chemicals lost in the English Channel from an Indonesian ship,
authorities said.
   Officials at the Marine Prefecture in this port city said winds
of up to 30 knots made the search impossible.
   In London, scientist Paul Johnston said a huge area of the
channel would be polluted and fish wiped out if one of the
containers holding six tons of Lindane insecticide leaked into the
water. ``It would be an environmental disaster,'' said Johnston, a
research fellow of the Greenpeace environmental organization at
London University's Queen Mary College.
   Police at St. Peter Port, chief town of Guernsey in the Channel
Islands, said the British Ministry of Agriculture alerted police in
the region to watch out for the containers.
   They said the containers were lost March 13 when the 263-ton
Perintis, a former landing craft built in Australia in 1945, sank in
a storm 35 miles northwest of Guernsey.
   The 11 Indonesian crewmen were rescued by helicopter but one died
later. The vessel was bound for Jakarta from Hamburg, West Germany.
   The Agriculture Ministry said a 40-foot container of Lindane
insecticide was located Wednesday but lost the next day by a French
naval patrol boat towing it between the Channel Islands and
Cherbourg.
   French officials said the minehunter La Clia would try Monday to
find the Lindane container, believed to be resting at the bottom of
the channel.
</TEXT>
