<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--AsiaDisasters     03-19 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Asia Disasters,0175</SECOND>
<HEAD>Asian Natural Disasters Linked to Environment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Asia suffered a terrible year of natural
disasters in 1988 stemming in part from environmental destruction,
especially deforestation, according to a U.N. report made available
Sunday.
   The report by the U.N. Economic and Social Commission for Asia
and the Pacific chronicled massive flooding in Bangladesh, Thailand
and Pakistan and drought in China.
   It linked the natural disasters with general environmental
ravages, especially large-scale deforestation.
   ``The phenomena of floods, mudslides, even earthquakes can be
directly related to deforestation,'' the report said.
   The commission, which described 1988 as ``a terrible year,'' said
major environmental problems faced by Asian countries included soil
erosion, loss of deserts and industrial pollution.
   The report was included in an annual survey of the region. It
will be presented at the organization's yearly conference, which
begins in Bangkok on March 27. More than 1,000 delegates are
expected to attend the 10-day meeting.
   The group has urged that development strategies take into account
environmental factors.
</TEXT>
