<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Jews     03-19 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Jews,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jewish Leaders Gather For A Show Of Solidarity With Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Chaim Herzog on Sunday told hundreds
of Jewish leaders from 30 countries that he prayed their conference
of solidarity with Israel would help advance peace in the Middle
East.
   ``You have answered the call to show solidarity with Israel at a
time of stress and hope in which people of Israel face many fateful
decisions,'' Herzog told participants in a forum organized by Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir.
   ``Let's pray that this conference will represent a genuine
advance towards peace and political adjustment in this area,''
Herzog said in a speech at the president's residence in Jerusalem.
   Some people in the United States and Israel have criticized the
conference as a gimmick to boost Shamir's hard-line policies before
he makes a crucial trip to Washington next month.
   But some of the 1,100 people who arrived for the three-day forum
said they came to strenghten Israel as it faces the Palestinian
uprising in the occupied lands and international pressure to devise
a Middle East peace initiative.
   The Prime Minister's Conference of Jewish Solidarity begins
Monday.
   ``I don't think it's our responsibility or our business to tell
the Israeli government and people how and what to do. We have been
asked to come here not to ... give direction to policy but to put a
line to all those out there who say we no longer support Israel,''
said Abraham H. Foxman, national director of the New York-based
Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith.
   ``To show that we do stand behind the people, and the state, and
the government, but not specific policies, I think today is more
important than ever before,'' Foxman said in an interview.
   When Shamir, the 73-year-old leader of the right-wing Likud bloc,
visits Washington in April, his hard-line views are expected to come
under increasing pressure from U.S. officials. Shamir has repeatedly
criticized Washington's dialogue with the Palestine Liberation
Organization, insisting it is a terrorist organization.
   He also opposes the American ``land for peace'' formula.
   Shamir on Friday said peace plans he would take to the United
States do not include a territorial compromise on the West Bank and
Gaza Strip, territories occupied by Israel since 1967.
   Three left-wing opposition parties, which support talks with the
PLO and giving away at least some occupied land, were quick to
attack the conference, saying it would not represent the whole range
of Israeli opinion.
   ``The real multifaceted, piercing, dramatic dialogue taking place
within Israel would not be reflected there,'' Yossi Sarid of the
Citizens Right Movement said on Israel Television. ``It is
legitimate that the government seeks ... support, but then you
cannot present the conference as supporting the Israeli people or
the state as such.''
</TEXT>
