<SECOND>AM-Tanzania-Ivory Arrest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0743,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Charged With Illegally Exporting 70 Tons of Ivory</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS graf after 3rd graf ``If convicted, to ADD report did
not specify whether man from North or South Yemen. Pick up 4th graf ``According
to...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAR ES SALAAM, Tanzania (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man from Yemen has been charged
with illegally exporting 70 tons of elephant ivory worth $9.8
million, a newspaper said Sunday.
   A court also charged Mohamed Sulaiman Alfan Saturday with
unlawfully possessing 853 hippopotamus teeth valued at $224,
according to the Sunday News. Police said Alfan shipped the tusks on
March 7 to Dubai in the United Arab Emirates, according to the news
report.
   If convicted, Alfan faces a possible 14 years in prison under
Tanzania's Economic and Organized Crime Control Act.
   The report did not specify whether Alfan came from North or South
Yemen, both on the southern tip of the Arabian peninsula.
   According to East African conservationists, the United Arab
Emirates has become the major distributing center for illegal
elephant ivory.
   High international prices for ivory continue to fuel widespread
poaching that already has cut Africa's elephant population in half
since the late 1970s, according to a 1987 U.N. Environmental study.
   In January, the government intercepted 184 elephant tusks being
smuggled out of the country by former Indonesian Ambassador Hussein
Joesoef. No legal action was taken against the diplomat, but the
government asked him immediately to leave the country.
