<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-89 1823EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-19 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow in Rockies; Cold in Upper Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy snow fell Sunday over portions of the Rockies and bitter
cold weather set records in Michigan and Wisconsin, but most of the
nation enjoyed relatively mild, dry weather.
   Ten inches of snow fell at the Park West ski area in Utah, and a
snow advisory was in effect for elevations above 6,000 feet in the
Utah mountains. A snow advisory also was posted for southwest
Wyoming and the mountains of Colorado.
   The tail end of a Pacific storm brought only light precipitation
to northern California, but officials there rejoiced that the
weekend storm had brought vital rainfall to the drought-plagued
region.
   ``Conditions are still far below normal in too many areas to say
the drought is over,'' said Suzanne Butterfield, statewide drought
coordinator for the California Department of Water Resources. ``But
it has eased considerably everywhere, with the exception of the
Central Coast and San Joaquin Valley.''
   Showers and thunderstorms were widely scattered across the
south-central United States, but rainfall was generally not heavy.
Dry weather prevailed over much of the rest of the country and skies
were fair to partly sunny most places east of the Mississippi.
   A cold front in the Southwest brought brisk winds to parts of
Southern California and a wind advisory was posted for desert and
mountain areas. Gusts to 50 mph were reported in the Mojave Desert.
   Temperatures were generally below freezing from Montana through
the Great Lakes region to northern New England, and in the 70s and
80s across parts of the Southwest and Southeast.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 19
degrees at Grand Forks, N.D., to 88 degrees at Tampa, Fla.
   Low temperature records were set in Alpena, Mich., where it was 7
below zero; Green Bay, Wis. (5 below); Marquette, Mich. (11 below);
Muskegon, Mich. (5 degrees); Rochester, Minn. (5 below); and
Traverse City, Mich. (4 below).
   The forecast for Monday included snow over the central high
plains and the Great Lakes, scattered snow showers over the central
plateau and the central Rockies and rain from western Kansas and
northwestern Texas through the lower and middle Mississippi Valley
to the Appalachians. Fair to partly sunny skies were expected across
the rest of the nation.
   High temperatures were expected to be below 50 from the northern
half of the plateau region through the northern and central plains
to New England; in the upper teens to lower 30s from eastern Montana
through the upper Mississippi Valley to upper Michigan and across
northern Maine; into the 70s from southern and central California to
southwestern New Mexico and from southern and central Texas to
Florida and southern Georgia; and in the 80s in south central Texas
and across the Florida peninsula.
</TEXT>
