<FIRST>r a AM-BundyBones     03-19 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bundy Bones,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities To Test Bones Found At Bundy Burial Site</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPITOL REEF NATIONAL PARK, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities who unearthed
bones and an apparent clothing fragment at a site identified by
serial killer Ted Bundy hope to determine this week whether they
belonged to one of his victims.
   It is not yet clear whether the bones are those of a human being,
Wayne County Sheriff Kerry Ekker said.
   Ekker said the state medical examiner's office will receive the
bones on Monday or Tuesday, and try to determine whether they were
those of 17-year-old Nancy Wilcox, who disappeared from her Salt
Lake City neighborhood on Oct. 2, 1974.
   Forensic testing should be finished by Thursday or Friday, he
said.
   Bundy was executed Jan. 24 in Florida's electric chair. For years
he had claimed he was innocent of all wrongdoing, but in the days
before he died, he confessed to killing at least 23 women in several
Western states.
   In Utah, he said, he had killed eight girls and women. He
identified only three, among them Wilcox, who he said was buried
near Capitol Reef National Park, 200 miles south of Salt Lake City.
   The sheriff also acknowledged that he was conferring with an
unidentified California psychic who claims to be able to pinpoint
the Wilcox burial site.
   ``I'm going to take a long shot. I'm desperate at this point,''
Ekker said. He added that if the medical examiner determines the
bones are not human, no further searches will be conducted.
   The bones, including what Ekker said appeared to be a shoulder
blade, were found by searchers Friday at one of three sites a mile
east of the park. Also found with the shoulder blade-like bone was a
fragment of what appeared to be a tan blouse.
   Bones at the first two sites were believed to be those of animals.
   The blouse ``was deteriorated to the point that it could have
been 14{ years ago'' when it was buried, Ekker added.
   Wilcox was wearing a blouse of unknown color when she
disappeared, Salt Lake County Sheriff's Detective Jerry Thompson
said.
   The other two women Bundy identified among his Utah victims were
Debi Kent, 17, who was last seen alive Nov. 8, 1974, at Bountiful's
Viewmont High School, and Susan Curtis, 15, who disappeared from the
Brigham Young University campus in Provo on June 27, 1975.
   Bundy also gave general directions to the graves of Kent and
Curtis before he was executed.
   The search for Curtis' remains is under way, and law enforcement
officers say they soon will look for Kent's body.
</TEXT>
