<FIRST>u i AM-NIreland-Killing     03-19 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NIreland-Killing,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunmen Kill Man In Belfast Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen killed a Roman Catholic
man in his north Belfast home on Sunday, police said, in what
appeared to be the latest in a series of retaliatory sectarian
slayings.
   The attackers burst into the man's house, shot him at close range
and escaped, police said. Press Association, the British domestic
news agency, identified the victim as 63-year-old David Braniff.
   He was the third person slain in north Belfast in four days, and
his death brings to 24 the number killed this year in Northern
Ireland's battle between Catholic and Protestant extremists.
   On Friday, Catholic civil servant Niall Davies, 42, was fatally
shot at his home, apparently in retaliation for the Irish Republican
Army killing the night before of Protestant Jackie Irvine, 49, shot
dead when two gunmen smashed their way into his house.
   The Belfast Brigade of the IRA, fighting to drive the British out
of the province, claimed Irvine was an active member of an outlawed
Protestant paramilitary group and said there were clear indications
he was involved in recent sectarian slayings of Catholics.
   The latest round of such slayings began Feb. 12 when Catholic
lawyer Patrick Finucane, who acted for clients allegedly involved
with the IRA, was killed by gunmen who stormed his home in north
Belfast.
   An outlawed Protestant paramilitary group, the Ulster Freedom
Fighters, claimed responsibility for his death, saying he was an IRA
officer. His widow denied the allegation.
   The IRA wants to unite predominantly Protestant Northern Ireland
with the 95 percent Catholic Republic of Ireland under socialist
rule.
   On Feb. 14, gunmen killed Sinn Fein councilman John Davey as he
drove to his home in the village of Glenduff 30 miles northwest of
Belfast. No group claimed responsibility.
   On Feb. 16, gunmen burst into a Protestant bar in Belfast and
opened fire, injuring five people. The Irish National Liberation
Army, a Marxist offshoot of the IRA, claimed responsibility.
   On March 8, IRA gunmen shot three Protestants to death outside a
gas station.
   On March 10, gunmen opened fire on two men leaving a Catholic bar
in west Belfast, killing one and wounding another.
</TEXT>
