<HEAD>Turkish Cypriot Police Scuffle with Protesting Greek Cypriot Women</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Greek Cypriots released. Pick
up 11th pvs, ``Achna has.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NIC1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LYMBIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Club-wielding Turkish Cypriot policemen
scuffled Sunday with Greek Cypriot women trying to breach Cyprus'
dividing Green Line to walk to their former homes in the
Turkish-occupied north of the island.
   Nine women were injured and 32 were detained as they tried to
break through a cordon of police and unarmed Turkish soldiers while
Turkish military helicopters buzzed overhead.
   Twenty-one other women and a male news photographer were detained
as about 3,500 protesters tried to cross the line patrolled by 2,000
U.N. peacekeepers. Helicopters of the U.N. force hovered low,
monitoring the women.
   Ten of the detainees were freed in the evening and the remainder
shortly before midnight at the Green Line checkpoint in Nicosia, the
Mediterranean island's divided capital, a police statement said.
   Earlier in the day at Lymbia, 19 miles southeast of Nicosia,
about 1,500 women carrying white flags and banners saying ``We come
in peace'' climbed up the hill to the whitewashed chapel of St.
George that serves as a Turkish Cypriot guard post. About 100
soldiers and policemen prepared to halt the advance.
   A banner hanging from the church said in English, ``Better apart
than dead!''
   About 100 U.N. peacekeepers crested the hill and separated the
Turkish Cypriots from the women. But the Turkish soldiers dodged
behind the U.N. troops and pushed the women down the hill.
   The other group, including 100 supporters from the United States
and western Europe, took over a church in the deserted village of
Akhna, 25 miles southeast of Nicosia.
   Achna has been deserted, except for a garrison, since Turkish
troops invaded northern Cyprus in 1974, ostensibly to protect the
Turkish Cypriot minority after a coup by Greek Cypriot militants
advocating union with Greece.
   The ``Women Walk Home'' march is spearheaded by women among
200,000 Greek Cypriot refugees, a third of the island's population,
who fled the north in the wake of the Turkish invasion. Some 40,000
Turkish Cypriots fled from the south.
   Turkey maintains 30,000 troops in the north, where Turkish
Cypriots proclaimed a breakaway state in 1983.
   The women want to arouse international indignation to put
pressure on Turkey. One of their leaders is Margaret Papandreou, the
estranged American wife of Greek Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou.
   ``The United Nations needs to be pushed. ... They are not doing
enough,'' she said Saturday.
   ``All the women are doing is demanding the right to go back to
their homes, a right which is guaranteed by the United Nations.''
</TEXT>
