<FIRST>r a AM-SwallowsReturn     03-19 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Swallows Return,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Swallows Make Their Official Return To Mission</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN CAPISTRANO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With bells heralding their
arrival, the swallows made their official return to Mission San Juan
Capistrano on Sunday, even though some of the birds were spotted at
least a month earlier.
   Thousands of tourists gathered at the site to get a glimpse of
the birds on their traditional St. Joseph's Day return, which falls
this year on Palm Sunday.
   The swallows were sparse, though, when 94-year-old Paul Arbiso
began his annual rite of tolling the mission courtyard bells at 7:57
a.m.
   ``For the air fare that I paid from New York, I wanted swarms,''
said Colleen Dunn-Holzworth, 21, of New York City, a Rutgers student
who came to Southern California for spring break.
   On Saturday, the 31st Annual Swallows Parade attracted an
estimated 2,000 spectators, said sheriff's Deputy Dennis Duncan.
   First accounts of the swallows coming to San Juan Capistrano on
their spring migration northward date back to 1776. That was the
year Father Junipero Serra founded the picturesque mission as part
of Spain's effort to spread the Roman Catholic faith _ and the
influence of Spain _ in the New World.
   Legend has it that the swallows have failed to arrive in
Capistrano once, in 1935, when they were held up by a storm.
   The official arrival of the swallows wasn't Southern California's
power landing this weekend. That distinction belonged to the space
shuttle Discovery.
   But John and Minerva Esquivel, who moved to Bakersfield recently
from San Antonio, Texas, went out of their way for the event, even
bypassing a hometown turnoff on Highway 58 that would have taken
them right to the shuttle's landing site at Edwards Air Force Base.
   ``We're kind of discovering California. We figured it was either
the space shuttle or the swallows,'' John Esquivel said.
   Despite the high expectations, however, on Sunday television
camera crews had to resort to throwing pebbles at the mission walls
to get the birds to take flight for the proper dramatic effect.
   George Chauncey of Las Vegas craned a home video camera around
and around, looking for at least one good swallow flight to record.
   ``I'm not disappointed. Why be disappointed? I've got my health.
It's nice weather. And I might get some good pictures,'' Chauncey
said.
   At least one bird-watcher said the swallows actually got a
one-month head start on the tourists.
   The first of the birds reached Southern California in February
from their winter homes in Argentina and other South American
countries, said Sandy Wohlgemuth, a birder with the Audubon Society
Los Angeles.
   The birds' numbers at the mission have dwindled in recent years,
and urban sprawl has covered much of the area, but they still find
places to flock, Magalousis said.
   ``Swallow's day is one of those popular things that most bird
watchers don't pay much attention to,'' said Wohlgemuth. ``But you
can't knock it or try to debunk it. After all, how many times does a
bird get in the news?''
</TEXT>
