<HEAD>Fonda: Rob Lowe Should Run For Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Rob Lowe is so good at charming a room full
of women, Jane Fonda says, that ``he should run for political office
someday.''
   In an article about Lowe in the April issue of Cosmopolitan
magazine, Fonda said of the handsome star: ``He's a phenomenon, much
like a young Frank Sinatra in the way he works the women in the
audience ... He'd make a good politician.''
   Lowe, 25, rose to fame as part of the so-called brat pack of
young, new actors in films like ``St. Elmo's Fire,'' ``The
Outsiders,'' and ``About Last Night.''
   He also made a name for himself with a string of romances with
high-profile women like Princess Stephanie of Monaco and Fawn Hall,
ex-secretary to Oliver North, on trial for his role in the
Iran-Contra affair.
   Lowe himself had a few less-than-politic comments on Ms. Hall.
   He told Cosmopolitan he was busy making a film during the
Iran-Contra hearings, ``so I wasn't aware of all the ins and outs
the way I would have been if I'd been reading the papers every day.
I knew Fawn had something going, and I wasn't sure what, but I knew
she was real tall and blond and stuffed documents in her underwear.''
   He added, ``Well, she swears to me she put them in her boots.''
   Lowe said they dated several times and now are just friends.
