<FIRST>r a AM-Lawyers-Restitution     03-19 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lawyers-Restitution,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Joel Steinberg Client Among Those Receiving State Restitution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH EDWARDSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Convicted child-killer Joel Steinberg is one
of 26 New York state lawyers whose clients were awarded a total of
$1 million from a state fund to compensate the victims of
unscrupulous lawyers, the executive director of the fund said Sunday.
   Steinberg's client, Stephen Liss, was awarded $400 from the fund
to compensate him for money he placed in escrow with Steinberg to
settle a lawsuit for his sister, said Frederick Miller of the state
Clients' Security Fund.
   ``Mr. Steinberg has not responded,'' said Miller. ``We sent him a
claim. ... It could very well be he still has the money (in
escrow.)''
   Steinberg was convicted Jan. 30 of first-degree manslaughter in
the Nov. 5, 1987, death of 6-year-old Lisa Steinberg, whom he had
raised with his companion, Hedda Nussbaum. He faces a maximum eight
and one-third to 25-year prison term when he is sentenced on Friday.
   Miller said the missing escrow money was delivered to Steinberg
``shortly before his arrest in connection with Lisa.''
   Steinberg, who was disbarred last year, was one of 26 lawyers _
all now dead or disbarred _ whose clients received awards from the
fund in the last three months, said Miller.
   Every practicing attorney in the state contributes $50 every two
years to finance the Clients' Security Fund, which provides up to
$100,000 coverage to individual clients and $200,000 for estates and
trusts with two or more beneficiaries. Since 1982, the fund has
returned more than $9 million to victims of dishonest lawyers.
   Another award involved the largest loss ever reported to the
fund: the alleged embezzlement of $1.1 million by Manhattan attorney
Peter Schmidt.
   Schmidt, who is believed to have fled the country with his
clients' money, was disbarred in February and is the object of an
international police search, said Miller.
   His client, Constantin Duba of Austria, gave him $1.1 million to
be placed in escrow. The money was to be used to eliminate single
room occupancy restrictions on some New York City real estate so
that maids' quarters could be converted into a penthouse apartment,
said Miller.
   Duba was awarded $100,000, the largest monetary award for
individual clients, Miller said.
   Two other claims are pending against Schmidt, including one
involving more than $2 million, said Miller.
</TEXT>
