<HEAD>Columbia Scraps Plans For Dinner Honoring Lorenzo</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines' embattled boss Frank Lorenzo
will not be honored at a Columbia College dinner at which he was to
receive a top alumni award, the school announced.
   The college, an undergraduate school at Columbia University here,
scrapped plans for the annual dinner, which was to be held Thursday,
``because the current emotional climate in the labor dispute between
Eastern Airlines and its Machinists' union makes it impossible to
guarantee an atmosphere appropriate to such a celebratory event,''
according to a statement.
   Asked Friday if there were plans to withdraw Lorenzo's John Jay
Award, which is awarded to prominent alumni for their achievements
and service to the college, spokesman Fred Knubel pointed to the
statement's last sentence, which read:
   ``The board of directors of the Columbia College Alumni
Association will decide on next steps at its fall meeting.''
   New York Newsday reported Saturday that the announcement came
amid reports that a protest was being planned to disrupt Thursday's
dinner, which costs at least $200 to attend.
   About 350 people, including five other award recipients, were
expected to attend. Proceeds go to the John Jay National Scholarship
Program.
   Although most of the outcry focused on Lorenzo's business
practices and the strike _ which began March 4 _ by 8,500 Eastern
mechanics and ground service workers, protest organizers also noted
that while Lorenzo was a student at Columbia in 1959, he was caught
in a ballot stuffing scheme.
   He was barred from ever voting again in a school election,
Newsday said.
