<FIRST>r a AM-Blind-Hostages 1stLd-Writethru a0750 03-19 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Blind-Hostages, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0750,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Free Two Children, Kill One Captor, Capture Other</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to UPDATE that Hill was shot in face; INSERTS
1 graf after 9th graf, `Hill, 49...,' to UPDATE with details of Hill's
blindness.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RHONDA HILLBERY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>APPLE VALLEY, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A blind escaped murderer was shot to
death and his partner captured early Sunday when police stormed a
townhouse and freed two children who had been held hostage for more
than a day.
   The blind fugitive, Larry Hill, was holding a knife to the throat
of 6-year-old Cameo Platt when police shot him in the face,
authorities said. The girl and her brother, 8-year-old Dominic, had
been held hostage since Friday afternoon at their home in this
Minneapolis suburb.
   ``The children seemed perfectly fine when we found them,'' police
Capt. Terry Cook said. ``They cried and said they missed their
mother.''
   Hill's accomplice, Willie Johnson, was taken into custody, police
said. He suffered a minor injury and was treated at a hospital
before being jailed, police Chief Lloyd Rivers said.
   Hill escaped from Stillwater State Prison outside St. Paul on
Friday morning while being escorted by two guards to a medical
office, where he had an appointment to get a replacement glass eye.
   Johnson, wearing a Halloween mask, met Hill at the office and the
two men disarmed the guards, tied them up and fled, police said.
   They then went to the townhouse of Lois Platt, the children's
mother, who had corresponded with Hill in prison. Her sister-in-law,
Peggy Platt, said Lois Platt broke off the relationship more than 18
months ago when she discovered Hill had been convicted of strangling
his girlfriend.
   Peggy Platt said she didn't believe the two had ever met face to
face before Friday.
   Hill, 49, was sentenced to 27 years in prison for second-degree
murder in 1982 and had prior convictions for two counts of rape, as
well as robbery, criminal sexual assault, burglary and illegal
handgun possession, according to Tom Dowdle, associate warden at the
Stillwater prison.
   LeRoy Siegel, assistant to the warden that the Stillwater prison,
said Hill's medical records indicate he became legally blind in the
early 1980s as a result of glaucoma. His vision later grew
progressively worse, officials said.
   Police identified Johnson, his accomplice, as a former Stillwater
inmate who served a five-year sentence for aggravated assault. He
was returned to prison for violating parole but was released in
January.
   Police negotiated with the men throughout the day Saturday as
more than 100 SWAT officers ringed the building. Apple Valley police
were joined by officers from surrounding communities, state and
county agencies and the FBI.
   ``Basically, they said they had to be allowed to leave. If they
didn't, they were going to throw a dead child out,'' Cook said.
   At one point, police seized Lois Platt when she was sent by the
the two men to start a car in what authorities described as an
escape attempt. Cook said she struggled with officers when they
refused to allow her to return to her children.
   Platt was taken to a hospital for treatment of exhaustion and
stress. She left the hospital late Saturday night and went to a
relative's house, Rivers said.
   Finally, at 1:30 a.m. Sunday, police decided to storm the
building when one of the children came out to pick up soft drinks
that authorities had sent to the townhouse, Cook said.
   Police threw at least two stun grenades into the house and a
special weapons and tactics team went in.
   ``We basically had a hard decision to make as to when the best
opportunity would present itself and we had to be ready to go when
it did,'' Cook said. ``As you know, we were dealing with some very
desperate men. It was unacceptable to allow the men to leave with
the children.''
</TEXT>
