<FIRST>u i AM-Palestinians 1stLdWriethru a0735 03-19 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Palestinians, 1st Ld Wriethru, a0735,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Threat to Assassinate Palestinians Contacting Israeli Leaders</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 5th pvs bgng: ``We consider... with
Palestinians meeting with Israelis. Pick up 6th pvs: Guerrillas of Fatah-Uprising...
ADDS two grafs, comment on U.S.-PLO talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS FARES</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dissident Palestinian Fatah-Uprising
guerrilla group threatened Sunday to assassinate Palestinians who
make direct contact with Israeli leaders.
   In a statement sent to The Associated Press, Fatah-Uprising
particularly mentioned people ``considered by the enemy close to the
Palestine Liberation Organization.'' It gave no names in the threat,
which apparently was designed to jeopardize PLO chief Yasser
Arafat's peace initiative.
   Fatah-Uprising, a Syrian-backed group led by Col. Saeed Mousa,
broke away from Arafat's mainstream Fatah movement in 1983.
   Its statement said that as the 15-month-old Palestinian uprising
in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip continues ``some
Palestinian personalities are conducting contacts and meetings with
the enemy which may lead to disastrous results.
   ``We consider these meetings an attempt to liquidate the
uprising. Therefore, we stress that the guns of the Palestinian
revolution will put an end to the life of anybody who may be tempted
to abuse the destiny of the Palestinian people and its sacred
cause,'' said the statement signed by Mousa's deputy, Khaled
al-Omlah.
   On Friday, Arafat spokesman Bassam Abu Sharif said several
Palestinians have been meeting with the Israelis.
   In an interview with the Paris-based Arabic Radio Monte Carlo he
named Gaza lawyer Fayez Abu Rahme; Elias Freij, mayor of Bethlehem;
Hanna Siniora, editor of a Palesinian newspaper, and Faisal
Husseini, recently released after months of detention by Israel. Abu
Sharif said the four were not PLO members but were in contact
Arafat's movement.
   Guerrillas of Fatah-Uprising infiltrated Israel from southern
Jordan on Friday in another bid to torpedo Arafat's peace efforts.
Jordan said its security forces later arrested the guerrillas.
   Arafat in December renounced terrorism and recognized Israel in
an attempt to open negotiations with the Jewish state, but Israeli
leaders so far have rejected his overtures.
   Arafat told the Italian newspaper La Repubblica last week that he
is willing to go to Jerusalem to pursue peace talks provided he gets
``full consent'' from Arab countries.
   The announcement drew sharp criticism from Fatah-Uprising and the
Damascus-based Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General
Command, which described Arafat as ``a traitor and an imperialist
agent.''
   Another guerrilla group, the Democratic Front for the Liberation
of Palestine, called on Arab countries Sunday to exert ``extreme
pressure'' on the United States to accept the establishment of a
Palestinian state.
   In a statement sent to The Associated Press in Nicosia, Cyprus,
it said its Politburo member Hisham Abu-Ghosh made the call at a
rally in Tripoli, Libya. The rally marked the 20th anniversary of
the Marxist group, a member of the PLO.
   The statement referred to the expected resumption of talks
between U.S. representatives and the PLO and said: ``The dialogue
between the PLO and the U.S. administration is not an end in itself.
   ``The Americans have to stop prevaricating in Israel's favor and
accept convening an international peace conference as a viable
framework for settlement,'' it said.
</TEXT>
