<FIRST>u i AM-Flight103 2ndLd-Writethru a0755 03-19 0789</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight 103, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0755,0805</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Urged To Tell All About Flight 103 Bomb Warnings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 6 grafs with newspaper report on identity of bomber, report
on security violations at Heathrow. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Demands for an independent inquiry into Britain's
handling of warnings received before the bombing of Pan Am Flight
103 will grow until the government explains its actions, an
opposition party leader said Sunday.
   Also Sunday, the government acknowledged that a December warning
about possible bombs on airliners was not mailed until after Jan. 1
_ at least 11 days after the Pan Am jet blew up and crashed, killing
270 people.
   ``We cannot afford `bag it and bin it' policies of British
official secrecy on matters of security which affect every air
traveler across the world,'' said Paddy Ashdown, leader of the
centrist Social and Liberal Democratic Party.
   Transport Secretary Paul Channon ``must come clean on all the
circumstances surrounding the advance warning,'' Ashdown said in a
statement.
   ``Unless he comes to the House of Commons at the earliest
opportunity next week and is competely candid in every detail, the
demand for an official inquiry on both sides of the Atlantic will
become irresistible,'' he said.
   Those demanding an independent inquiry include the opposition
Labor Party and relatives of those killed when Flight 103 exploded
over Lockerbie, Scotland, Dec. 21 on a flight to New York.
Investigators say the disaster was caused by a bomb concealed in a
radio-cassette player packed in luggage in the plane's hold.
   Channon said Sunday he told Parliament ``as much as it is in my
power to tell.'' Government ministers ``should not go around
revealing things that might be against the national interest,'' he
told the British Broadcasting Corp.
   Channon said he welcomed U.S. Transportation Secretary Samuel
Skinner's decision to send top aides to London and Frankfurt, West
Germany, to assess aviation security. Skinner said he wants his
officials to determine, among other things, when and how warnings
were made against Pan Am flights last year.
   ``The investigators have been working extremely closely with the
Americans at all stages, and I think if they come over here, and the
investigators have further talks with them, that can only be a very
good thing,'' Channon said.
   ``There is keen public concern in the United States and in this
country about the progress of this investigation and it's not
surprising that people should wish to come over and have further
talks.''
   The Transport Department confirmed last week it prepared a
warning dated Dec. 19 that included photographs of a bomb hidden in
a radio-cassette player but did not mail it until after Christmas.
   But on Sunday, a department spokesman said the warning was not
sent until the New Year because the accompanying photos had to be
prepared. The spokesman, who demanded anonymity, did not give the
exact date of the mailing.
   Channon has said the letter was of little importance because
similar information had been sent out a month earlier by the U.S.
Federal Aviation Administration and by West Germany. Flight 103
originated in West Germany and changed planes at London's Heathrow
Airport before setting out for New York.
   Two London newspapers, The Observer and The Sunday Telegraph,
reported Sunday that the Dec. 19 warning carried several important
details that would have helped security people spot a rigged
radio-cassette player.
   Another London newspaper, the weekly Sunday Express, reported
that the man who made the bomb is a Libyan known to international
security officials as ``The Professor'' because of his knowledge of
explosives.
   The Sunday Express attributed its information to unidentified
detectives. It did not identify the man by name.
   The Express also said a Lebanese student, 21-year-old Khalid
Jaafar, of Dearborn, Mich., unwittingly carried the bomb onto the
flight in a radio-cassette player given to him as a gift. It did not
say who gave it to him.
   The FBI has questioned Jaafar's father, Nazir, who has denied
earlier reports in U.S. and British newspapers that his son may have
brought the bomb on the plane without knowing it.
   Also Sunday, ABC News reported that the bombing of Flight 103 was
surrounded by serious mistakes in security at Heathrow Airport. The
network said it obtained a memo from the British Transport
Department dated Dec. 29 which conceded that baggage coming from
Frankfurt was transferred directly to the jet headed for New York
without being screened.
   The memo also said a passenger arriving late at the departure
gate was not allowed to fly to New York, but his baggage stayed on _
a violation of security rules. The memo did not say who the
passenger was or give other details, ABC said.
</TEXT>
