<FIRST>r a AM-FourShot     03-19 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Four Shot,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Child Remains Critical, Another Stable After Saturday Shootout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST ORANGE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gunman who killed one child and
wounded two others had a history of mental problems and was a target
of frequent harassment by adolescents in his suburban neighborhood,
according to neighbors and police.
   The gunman, George Proctor, was shot and killed by a police
officer Saturday night after he went on the shooting spree in this
bedroom community about 10 miles west of New York City.
   Eight-year-old Kareem Davis remained in critical condition Sunday
with a gunshot wound to the head, according to Bob Arnold, associate
administrator of University Hospital in Newark.
   A second child, 12-year-old Joshua Velez, was listed in stable
condition and transferred Sunday to Children's Hospital, Arnold
said. Velez also was shot in the head and the wound threatens his
eyesight, authorities said.
   Inside the building where he lived, Proctor shot 9-year-old Ivory
Smith, who died Saturday night from her injuries, authorities said.
   Proctor then emerged and began firing his .32 caliber gun,
witnesses said.
   Both Velez and Davis were outside the building and were hit by
shots from Proctor's gun, police and witnesses said.
   Police Officer Thomas Smith, from the adjacent town of Orange,
was on a routine patrol at the border of the two towns when he heard
the shots.
   He exchanged fire with Proctor, who was hit with four rounds,
West Orange Police Chief Edward Palardy said.
   ``He (Smith) will definitely receive a letter of commendation
from my office for his actions,'' Palardy said.
   Smith was released from Orange Memorial Hospital on Sunday after
being treated for a grazing gunshot wound on the head, Palardy said.
   Proctor, 60, was a frequent target of harassment from older
teen-agers in the area, according to neighbors.
   ``Just prior to the tragedy, two young men threw stones at his
car,'' Palardy said, adding that the victims were not involved in
the incident.
   Proctor was a long-time resident of the neighborhood who worked
as a janitor at Union County College. He was hospitalized for nine
years for mental instability, according to the police chief.
   ``His family said he had emotional and mental problems,'' Palardy
said. ``I'm not sure of the specifics but they said they were
serious.''
   Palardy said he did not know when the man had been released.
   Proctor had no prior criminal record, but the gun he used
Saturday was not registered, Palardy said.
</TEXT>
