<FIRST>r a AM-CancerTransplant 1stLd-Writethru a0791 03-19 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cancer Transplant, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0791,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>Once-Terminal Woman Goes Home, Cancer Free, after Transplants</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to correct cycle designator.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman once considered terminally ill by
doctors is cancer-free after receiving an experimental, four-organ
abdominal transplant, hospital officials say.
   Diana Hancock, 40, was admitted to Presbyterian-University
Hospital of Pittsburgh on Jan. 12 with an inoperable tumor on her
liver bile duct.
   The following day, surgeons replaced her liver, pancreas,
duodenum, and two sections of her small intestine. Her stomach was
removed but not replaced, requiring her to eat six small meals a day
spaced an hour or two apart.
   Ms. Hancock, a computer operator from Burlington, Wis., headed
home free of malignancy Saturday, hospital officials said. She is
among 11 once-terminal patients who are cancer-free after having
four of their abdominal organs replaced.
   Ms. Hancock said the transplant has given her ``a new lease on
life.''
   ``Now I have all the hope in the world,'' she said, adding that
she must return to Pittsburgh in two months for a check-up.
   The transplants, believed to be the first of their kind, have
been performed on 10 men and three women since June at
Presbyterian-University Hospital. Two patients died.
</TEXT>
