<FIRST>r a AM-PanAmRelatives     03-19 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pan Am Relatives,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Relatives Say Warnings Came too Late in Pan Am Bombing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK SEAVY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRUMBULL, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives of victims of the bombing of Pan
Am Flight 103 said Sunday they are outraged by recent disclosures
about terrorism warnings made by federal officials before the
tragedy.
   ``It's absolutely ridiculous that they're three months too
late,'' said Jan Coyle of Wallingford, whose 20-year-old daughter,
Patricia, was among the 270 people who died in the Dec. 21 crash.
``To comprehend that this could have been avoided is unforgivable.''
   Coyle, clutching photographs of her daughter, a junior at Boston
College, was among about 100 people who attended a meeting of the
Victims of Flight 103 at the Marriott.
   The meeting was organized in the wake of disclosures that at
least six Federal Aviation Administration security bulletins issued
between Oct. 26 and Dec. 19 warned of the type of attack that
eventually caused Flight 103 to crash. The jet blew up over
Lockerbie, Scotland, and investigators have traced the bombing to
plastic explosives hidden inside a radio-cassette player.
   Many of the relatives wore white buttons emblazoned with blue
lettering saying ``Pan Am 103 _ The Truth Must be Known.'' Yet the
facts surrounding the bombing, which are slowly being released, have
provided little relief to those whose loved ones died on the plane.
   ``The more I hear, the less I want to hear,'' said Richard G.
Monetti of Cherry Hill, N.J., who wore a button bearing a picture of
his smiling son, Richard Monetti, a 20-year-old junior at Syracuse
University when he died.
   ``Frankly I had hoped the plane had a structural defect and fell
apart and my son died because it was an unfortunate accident. We'd
be devastated, but we'd pick up the pieces and we'd go on. The more
I hear the more it sounds like that if anything had gone right it
would have been avoided.''
   Many at the meeting questioned why some people avoided the
bombing by canceling their reservations. Marina DeLarracoechea, a
native of Bilbao, Spain, whose 39-year-old sister, Nieves, was a
stewardess aboard the flight, said there were 169 empty seats on the
plane and discount tickets for the flight had been sold.
   ``All the parties and all the people that are responsible for
this lack of action should be brought to justice because on all
their heads are the lives of 270 people,'' Ms. DeLarracoechea said.
   In recent weeks, relatives have urged the Senate Subcommitte on
Transportation to beef up security at airports, return property of
victims of Flight 103 and reveal the status of security before the
bombing.
   ``If we do not change this (terrorist) policy we will see these
terrorist acts over and over again because the terrorists will not
go away,'' said Paul Hudson of New York, whose 16-year-old daughter,
Melina, died in the crash.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
