<FIRST>r a AM-EasternFallout     03-19 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern Fallout,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Crisis Forces Tour Operator to File for Bankruptcy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A large tour operator closely linked with
crippled Eastern Airlines has been forced to file for bankruptcy
protection, and a travel industry executive said rumors of other
such failures abound.
   Tour operators are suffering as a result of fallout from the
Eastern crisis that also has hit some commuter airlines. Precision
Airlines of Manchester, N.H., one of the commuter carriers that
feeds into Eastern flights, recently suspended all operations and
furloughed 350 workers, citing a 70 percent drop in passenger
traffic.
   The Machinists union's strike against Miami-based Eastern,
supported by most of its pilots and flight attendants, is now in its
third week. Eastern filed for protection from creditors under
Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy law on March 9, and went
shopping Sunday for the new pilots it needs to survive the draining
strike.
   Last week Flyfaire Inc., one of the biggest U.S. tour operators
specializing in Caribbean vacation packages, sought protection under
Chapter 11 itself in a reflex action.
   ``Rumors have been flying'' of other tour operators also seeking
refuge in bankruptcy protection, said Sue Shapiro, president of the
Greater Independent Association of National Travel Agents in New
York. ``There's an obvious concern about anyone tied in with
Eastern.''
   Tour operators sell packages to travel agents. They function as
wholesalers between airlines and hotels on one side and travel
agents and consumers on the other.
   Flyfaire, based in Hawthorne, N.Y., used Eastern flights as the
basis for around 70 percent of its tour packages. The tour operator,
which says it is owed about $1.5 million by Eastern, was squeezed by
the airline's bankruptcy action.
   ``It became a nightmare,'' Flyfaire President Joseph Garzilli
said in a telephone interview, likening his company's plight to
being on an Eastern Airlines plane that crashed.
   Flyfaire's financial losses are compounded by the fact that it
cannot operate normally without Eastern flying a full schedule, he
said.
   The tour operator cut its staff from 230 to 50 after it filed for
bankruptcy in a New Jersey court, Garzilli said. The 16-year-old
company, with offices in New Jersey, Florida, Los Angeles,
Philadelphia, Pittsburgh, Detroit and other locations, had been
pulling in about $110 million a year in sales.
   Now, Garzilli's company must queue up with Eastern's other
unsecured creditors _ including banks, ticket holders, travel agents
and Eastern employees demanding paychecks _ whose financial exposure
is not backed by collateral. As the airline's bankruptcy proceedings
drag on, it could be weeks or months before they are paid.
   It was not immediately known how many other tour operators are
closely linked with Eastern the way Flyfaire is. Flyfaire's leading
competitor in Caribbean tours, Liberty Travel, mainly uses other
carriers.
   Ms. Shapiro said her group didn't know how many tied-in operators
could be affected by the Eastern bankruptcy. Spokesmen for the
United States Tour Operators Association and the American Society of
Travel Agents were unavailable for comment Sunday.
</TEXT>
