<FIRST>r a AM-TeenMurder     03-19 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teen Murder,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Neighbors Taunt Family Where Slain Girl Was Found</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VALLEY STREAM, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 40 angry friends and
relatives of a slain 13-year-old girl stood Sunday outside the house
where her body was found and taunted the family who lives there with
chants of ``devils.''
   The furious throng, which included the father, an aunt and an
uncle of the slain girl, Kelly Tinyes, shouted that the Golub family
would ``rot in hell.'' The verbal assault lasted about two hours.
   The Golubs had returned to the house at 6:30 p.m. Saturday for
the first time since the girl's death, when authorities ordered them
to vacate the house because it was the scene of a crime.
   Kelly's body was found March 4 in the basement of the Golub home
in Valley Stream on Long Island. She was seen entering the house a
day earlier.
   Nassau County Police Lt. Bill Krausch said police were ready to
make an arrest in the case, but that they deferred to the county
prosecutor, who wanted first to present evidence to the grand jury
on Wednesday.
   Krausch would not identify who was the target of the arrest.
However, police have said that the only suspects in the case were
two Golub brothers, Robert, 21, and John, 14.
   At about noon Sunday, when Robert left the house on foot, he was
followed by Kelly's father, Richard Tinyes, and the angry crowd.
   According to Nassau County police spokesman Officer Charles
Koller, a patroling police officer saw Golub being followed and
called for assistance.
   When Golub reached a grocery store, about six blocks from his
house, some of the mob repeatedly accused him of being a ``devil.''
   Eight police cars arrived, and officers protected Golub as he
left the store with his older sister, Adele, who had come to pick
him up in a car.
   The verbal lynching continued, with one member of the crowd
shouting at the sister, ``You are a devil for being with him.''
   Ms. Golub yelled, ``My brothers were innocent,'' before breaking
down into sobs and driving away in the car.
   At 12:20 p.m., as neighbors shouted that the house was filled
with devils, several family members _ Robert, Adele, John and their
mother, Elizabeth, left the house and drove away in one car.
   About 10 minutes later, their father, John Sr., left in a
separate car as somebody shouted, ``You're raising devils in the
house.''
   As he drove away, the neighbors applauded. The Golubs departed
``for parts unknown,'' said Koller.
</TEXT>
