<FIRST>r a AM-TVSwap     03-19 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-TV Swap,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Atlanta, Soviet TV Journalists To Swap Jobs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reporter and camera operator from an Atlanta
television station leave this week for six weeks in the Soviet
Union. Nothing unusual about that _ except that they'll be reporting
for Soviet television.
   The trip is part of a unusual job-swapping deal in which a Soviet
reporter will later spend six weeks at Atlanta station WXIA-TV.
   WXIA Reporter Simeon Smith, who is fluent in Russian, and
cameraman Richard Crabbe leave Tuesday for Tbilisi, Atlanta's sister
city in the Soviet Republic of Georgia.
   There they will work for Gostelradio, the government organization
that runs Soviet television.
   ``A lot of what we will be doing is comparative stuff between
life in Atlanta and life in Tbilisi,'' Smith said.
   When they return, they'll be accompanied by Nugzar Ruhadze, an
English-speaking Soviet reporter who will work at WXIA for six
weeks, reporting to Atlanta viewers.
   Ellen Mickiewicz, an Emory University professor and one of the
country's leading experts on Soviet television, said she believes
it's the first such exchange of reporters.
   Smith said he has been stockpiling features on life in Atlanta,
with stories ranging from Stone Mountain's new Megastore to AIDS
victims, the Atlanta Hawks pro basketball team, the homeless and an
affluent teen-age girl ``who has a closet that's as big as most
Russian apartments.''
   He said most of his work in Tbilisi will be relatively
apolitical, ``but if they have a hot story, like an earthquake, I'm
part of the team.''
   ``We told them, `If you want to censor Simeon, go for it,''' said
WXIA General Manager Harvey Mars, who made two trips to the Soviet
Union to set up the exchange. ``But just remember, when he comes
back, he tells all.''
   In the Soviet Union, each of the 15 republics has its own
newscast, which usually is broadcast twice, once in Russian and once
in the language of the Republic, which in the case of Tbilisi in the
Republic of Georgia is Georgian. There also is a national newscast.
   Most of Smith's work will be for the Georgia newscast, but some
may be used nationally. He will report in Russian, which will be
translated into Georgian.
</TEXT>
