<FIRST>u i AM-Belgium-NuclearEnergy     03-19 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Belgium-Nuclear Energy,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unions Urge Stricter Nuclear Safety Controls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A union umbrella group on Monday called
for tougher safety standards for nuclear power plants worldwide and
the creation of an ``independent'' international nuclear regulatory
agency.
   The Brussels-based International Confederation of Free Trade
Unions said the Vienna-based International Atomic Energy Agency was
``unsuited'' for regulatory activities. In a 40-page report, the
Confederation said the agency was ``compromised by its role in
promoting nuclear energy.''
   The report released Monday called for creation of a watchdog
group with powers to enforce binding safety standards and visit
nuclear plants unannounced. It also called for unions to participate
in setting and enforcing plant safety rules.
   The confederation is the non-communist world's largest union
umbrella group and claims to represent 87 million workers from 141
unions in 97 countries.
   The organization said the report reflected a desire for greater
openness in the nuclear power industry and called for regular
statements on all nuclear incidents.
   ``This report is neither pro-nuclear nor anti-nuclear. It's
pro-safety,'' Confederation Secretary General John Vanderveken said
in a statement released Monday.
   The report, released simultaneously in Brussels, London, Vienna
and New Delhi, will serve as a basis for talks on April 6 and 7
between the Confederation and the Atomic Energy Agency in Vienna.
</TEXT>
