<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Gotoh     03-19 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Gotoh,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Entrepreneur Dies Of Respiratory Failure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Noboru Gotoh, former president of the Japan Chamber
of Commerce and Industry and a leader in one of Japan's largest
business conglomerates, died of respiratory failure early Monday. He
was 72.
   Gotoh, a 1940 graduate of the Economics Department at Tokyo
University, in 1959 became president of the Tokyu Corp., a railway
that was the core of the Tokyu business group his father founded.
   Gotoh joined Tokyu Corp. in October 1945 after serving in the
Japanese army.
   Under Gotoh's guidance, the Tokyu business group expanded to 334
firms, including railways, real estate and construction firms,
department stores and hotels.
   Gotoh, who sustained an interest in pan-Pacific economic
cooperation, served since 1978 as chairman of the Japan Committee of
the Pacific Basin Economic Committee (PBEC), a forum of 850 company
representatives from 16 countries and areas, including the United
States, Australia, New Zealand, South Korea, Taiwan and Japan.
   In 1984, he was elected head of the Japan Chamber of Commerce and
Industry. He retired from the post in December 1987 for health
reasons and became an honorary president.
   Gotoh had been in and out of hospitals since he underwent surgery
for a stomach ulcer in May 1987.
   Gotoh is survived by his wife, Yoko, three sons and two daughters.
</TEXT>
