<FIRST>r f AM-Bronco-Samurai Bjt   03-19 0708</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bronco-Samurai, Bjt,0729</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bronco, Not Samurai, Feels Heat Of Government Probe</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It would be hard to tell from the amount of media
coverage that the vehicle under government investigation for
rollovers is the Ford Bronco II and not the Suzuki Samurai.
   It would also be hard to tell from the sales totals. Although the
government has never had a harsh word about the Samurai, its sales
are a tenth what they were before Consumer Reports magazine charged
last year that the boxy little four-wheel-drive vehicle tips over
too easily.
   The fate of the Samurai illustrates the power of the news media
to influence car-buying decisions, particularly the power of the
repeatedly televised videotapes showing the Samurai going up on two
wheels in high-speed maneuvers.
   Now Ford Motor Co. is waiting to see what will happen to sales of
its Bronco II following the announcement last week that it will be
investigated for rollovers by the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration.
   Most auto analysts predict the government's probe _ strictly
speaking, an engineering analysis _ will have little effect on
Bronco II sales, for two reasons:
   _Engineering analyses are routine. Fifty-five were under way as
of the end of February, the agency says. Of those, only some go on
to the next stage, the ``case level.'' And only some of those result
in determinations of safety defects.
   _The Bronco II has not received as much negative publicity as the
Samurai got, partly because the government did not release any
gripping videotapes of the Bronco II going up on two wheels.
   ``The power of the press really hit home in the Samurai
controversy. So far the Bronco is pretty far from that type of
situation,'' said Scott Merlis, an auto analyst at Morgan Stanley &amp;
Co.
   The Jeep-like Samurai was rolling along at sales of about 6,000 a
month when Consumer Reports magazine called a news conference on
June 2 to say it was giving the vehicle a not-acceptable rating. It
said the Japanese-built Samurai ``literally trips over its own
feet'' because of a narrow tread width, short wheelbase, light
weight and high center of gravity.
   Sales plunged to 2,199 in June. Suzuki responded with dealer
incentives that resulted in sharp price cuts, and sales rebounded to
6,327 in July and a record 12,208 in August.
   The automaker appeared to have come back from the brink. It got a
boost on Sept. 1 when the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration denied a recall petition by the Center for Auto
Safety, a Washington-based consumer group.
   The respite was short-lived, though, as sales plummeted to 560 in
September, 787 in October and 483 in November. They jumped to 2,483
in December before retreating to 263 in January and 472 in February.
   Sales of the bigger, heavier and more expensive Bronco II run
about 9,000 to 11,000 a month.
   Officials of Brea, Calif.-based American Suzuki say Samurai sales
have been hampered by several unrelated factors, including the
difficulties of introducing three other Suzuki models in the past
several months: the Sidekick, the Swift GTi and the Swift GLX.
   But they admit that last summer's publicity hurt. Sales of all
four Suzuki vehicles combined totaled less than 3,000 last month.
   ``We have seen a longer-term impact on the sales than we would
have hoped. I'm not sure there is one reporter who can write a story
about Suzuki without mentioning this issue,'' said Lynne M. Doll, a
spokeswoman with the company's public relations agency, Rogers &amp;
Associates.
   The government safety board said it chose to investigate the
Bronco II because statistics unearthed last year showed it had a far
higher rate of fatal rollovers than the Samurai.
   Clarence Ditlow, head of the Center for Auto Safety, said he
thinks the government missed some fatal rollovers involving the
Samurai while slightly overstating the Bronco II's. He says the
vehicles are equally bad. ``They both deserve to be investigated,''
he said in an interview last week.
   In fact, the government probe may not make much difference.
Unless the agency discovers serious rollover problems with the
Bronco II, its sales are likely to remain healthy. For the Samurai,
meanwhile, the damage is already done.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
