<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-89 1529EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-TickerTalk Bjt   03-19 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ticker Talk, Bjt,0648</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brokerage Chief Urges New Twist for IRAs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top Wall Street executive has begun a campaign
for a measure he says would stimulate savings without aggravating
the government's budget problems.
   William Schreyer, the chairman of Merrill Lynch &amp; Co., contends
that his idea would ``put some renewed sex appeal'' into individual
retirement accounts.
   At the same time, he says, it would help to pay in advance for
the future costs of health care and the well-being of the rapidly
growing numbers of older Americans.
   Schreyer's idea, put forward in speeches he has been giving this
month, is not to restore the tax breaks for IRA contributions that
were curtailed by the Tax Reform Act of 1986 _ not right away, at
least.
   Rather, he is proposing that IRA savers be given the right to
withdraw money from their accounts in the future for certain
purposes _ medical, educational and home ownership _ without having
to pay tax on the proceeds.
   Schreyer's argument starts from the premise that the nation needs
to increase its chronically low savings rate if it is going to be
able to bear the costs of supporting an aging population in the
decades ahead.
   But he also acknowledges a more immediate need to settle current
accounts that are out of whack.
   ``The deficit crisis is real,'' he says. ``We've got to find ways
to encourage increased savings that take little or nothing out of
the Treasury's hide now.''
   Of course, Schreyer is hardly a disinterested party in the debate
over tax policy. When IRAs were opened up to all working Americans
in 1982, they became lucrative products for firms like Merrill Lynch.
   In 1987, when deductions for contributions ended for married
couples making $50,000 or more a year, and individuals with incomes
of $35,000 and up, the flow of money into these accounts slowed
significantly.
   But does his idea have merit? At first glance, at least, it looks
like a tax break that would benefit upper-income people the most.
Hence, it wouldn't seem to have much chance of attracting support in
Congress.
   However, supporters of the idea point out, the situation isn't
quite that simple. All IRA withdrawals, except for the amount of
non-deductible contributions made by the well-to-do, are now subject
to tax.
   So under Schreyer's proposal, all American workers would have a
greater incentive to put as much money as possible in IRAs. The
interest, dividends and capital gains that now build up tax-free
inside IRAs would remain tax-free when they were taken out.
   What's more, the accounts could be used to plan not just for
retirement, but for other goals Schreyer describes as socially
desirable, including education, and to help shoulder the burden of
the mounting cost of health care.
   But the idea raises several tough questions. First of all, what
would it mean for future government budgets?
   If taxpayers were able to build up large new amounts of money
that the government could lay no claim to, might tax rates on other
income have to be raised, and new types of taxes be created?
   Furthermore, would IRA contributors totally buy the idea that
their money could actually never be taxed?
   Recent tax changes have tainted principles that once were thought
to be sacrosanct: For example, ``no taxes on taxes.'' Well, state
sales taxes no longer are deductible and the deduction for state
income taxes barely survived the last debate about changing the
rules.
   Schreyer's case is that the nation should be thinking long-term
in handling its finances. As legions of financial advisers have
pointed out in recent years, that is hard to do in a climate where
the tax rules are subject to frequent and seemingly limitless change.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890319-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-89 1644EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-ChannelOne Bjt   03-19 0762</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Channel One, Bjt,0786</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whittle Begins Research to Build Case for TV News Show for Schools</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students at two California high schools, Gahr and
nearby Cerritos, took a current events quiz last week, and the
results could help decide whether commercial television gets a place
in the classroom.
   The quizzes were part of a research effort designed to see if a
daily TV news show that includes paid advertising is helping
students learn.
   The nearly 2,000 students at Gahr High School in Cerritos,
Calif., have been able to watch the news show called Channel One for
the past two weeks on 91 new television sets given to the school and
installed in every classroom.
   The youngsters at Cerritos High School, whose enrollment numbers
and characteristics resemble those of its suburban Los Angeles
neighbor, haven't had a chance to see the news show but agreed to
take the quiz anyway.
   Whittle Communications LP, the Knoxville, Tenn.-based media
concern that developed Channel One, plans to tally the results from
these schools along with those from tests at the five other schools
in the Channel One project and their sister schools and see if the
show is helping educate students.
   Backers of the program are betting that the research will show a
significant difference in the results from the schools that have
been exposed to the show and those that have not.
   That could be a critical element in Whittle's efforts to persuade
other schools to sign up for the Channel One project. Whittle hopes
to expand the service to as many as 8,000 schools nationwide in the
fall of 1990.
   ``We expect to see real differences, and if we do it will be a
real plus for the program,'' Whittle chairman Christopher Whittle
said Friday in a telelphone interview.
   The main obstacle to the project appears to be the intense
opposition from children's advocates and some education groups who
say companies should not be allowed to pitch their products to an
essentially captive audience in school.
   Groups such as the National Association of Secondary School
Principals and the National Parent-Teacher Association have opposed
it.
   Peggy Charren, head of Action for Children's Television, a
Massachusetts-based children's advocacy group, said she thinks the
Channel One test has been orchestrated to gloss over the bad
precedent she says is being set of allowing commercials in
classrooms.
   ``The problem is we are selling children to advertisers ... They
think they are going to get enough kids buying enough products to
make the investment worthwhile,'' Mrs. Charren said.
   The test of Channel One began March 6 at Gahr and five others
schools _ Mumford High School in Detroit, Withrow High School in
Cincinnati, Eisenhower Middle School in Kansas City, Kan., Billerica
Memorial High School near Boston and Central High School in
Knoxville.
   Each school was given about $50,000 in televisions, video
recorders and a satellite dish to recieve a daily 12-minute news
show with up to two minutes of paid ads. The sponsors include Levi's
jeans, Snickers candy bars and Clearasil acne cream.
   In return, the schools are asked to play the show once each
school day.
   The test is to include five weeks of programs over a seven-week
period. Channel One has just begun a two-week hiatus for spring
break during which the producers hope to fine-tune the program.
   A typical news show relates the day's top stories and contains
features on subjects like the environment and the lifetsyles of
Soviet teen-agers.
   Last week, Channel One also carried a live 15-minute special
without commercials on the launch of the space shuttle Discovery.
   To test if the show is effective, Whittle plans to give quizzes
at all six schools and their sister schools in each district for
comparison.
   Students at Gahr and Cerritos got 29 multiple choice questions,
most of which came from information in the past week's shows.
   Whittle said his company is also conducting two other types of
studies to measure the effectiveness of the project.
   He said one involves group interviews with teachers or students
from the schools. The other involves telephone interviews with
students who have gotten their parent's permission to talk about the
commercials on the program.
   Whittle said the comparative quiz results, the group discussions
and the telephone polling will all figure in whether his company
invests more than $100 million in hardware alone that he said will
be required to go national.
   ``Five weeks isn't a very long time, but we ought to be able to
show some movement,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
