<SECOND>AM-Boston Rent, 1st Ld-Writethru,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: Boston Tenants Paying Highest Percentage of Income on Rent</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `The study...,' with 3 grafs to UPDATE with other
available cities (</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boston-area tenants pay a bigger chunk of their
income in rent than tenants in any other major city in the country,
while Houston residents pay the smallest, a new study says.
   A California research firm, Sound Advice, calculated that
Boston's median rent is $586 a month. That is about the same as San
Francisco, but the study found median incomes were lower in Boston,
so that while San Franciscans pay 19.5 percent of their income on
rent, Bostonians pay 21.3 percent.
   Renters in New York pay a median of $444 per month. Though the
rent is lower than San Francisco's, it amounts to about the same
percentage of income as renters in San Francisco pay, again because
New York incomes are lower, the study found.
   The figures are lower than actual market-rate rents because they
include subsidized apartments. Excluding subsidized apartments, the
Boston Redevelopment Authority figures the average rent in Boston
last year was $800 a month.
   Houston was ranked as the most economical of the 25 cities
surveyed in terms of percentage of income, with a monthly rent of
$346 _ about 13 percent of the median household income. It was
followed by Cincinnati, where the median rent is $322, or 13.5
percent of household income.
   Next to Boston, the least economical city was Los Angeles, where
median rents were $521, or 20.7 percent of income.
   The average of all 25 cities was $425 _ 18.5 percent of monthly
income.
   Median rents for other cities, along with the percentage that it
comprised of median income, included Cleveland, $380 and 13.8
percent; Chicago, $441 and 15.1 percent; Seattle, $419 and 15.3
percent; and Washington, $601 and 18.3 percent.
   The study touched a nerve in Boston, where rents have increased
64 percent since 1982. That includes a 6.1 percent rise last year
that was the biggest of any major metropolitan area except
Washington, according to the Bureau of Labor Statistics.
   Rents are skyrocketing in a city that already has one of the
highest median house prices in the nation, estimated as high as
$195,000.
   ``The simple fact is that people can't afford to buy homes,''
said Lewis Finfer, director of the Massachusetts Affordable Housing
Alliance. ``So the average blue-collar, lower-middle-class person is
staying in rentals longer, making more competition for rental units.
There's not enough production of affordable housing.''
   ``We've looked at some of the rent indexes, and the Northeast in
general and Boston in particular have had above-average rent
increases over the past six to eight years,'' said William Apgar,
acting director of the Joint Center for Housing Studies at Harvard
University.
   Economists say the middle class is caught in a dilemma of not
being able to save for a down payment because of high rents, but
making too much money to qualify for subsidized rentals.
   Would-be homebuyers Charlene and Stephen Tobey have been saving
for a down payment for more than three years and expect it will take
at least two more.
   ``House prices have risen so fast that it's terribly hard for
first-time home buyers,'' Mrs. Robey told The Sunday Boston Globe.
   Edward E. Zuker, president of the Rental Housing Association of
the Greater Boston Real Estate Board, said there is virtually no
construction of rental apartments in the range just below Boston's
median level.
   He said city leaders must try to work with community leaders in
encouraging construction of affordable housing.
   ``Everyone's for affordable housing as long as it's not in their
back yard,'' he said. ``There's a lot of lip service, but not a lot
of action.''
</TEXT>
