<FIRST>r f AM-UniversalFoods     03-19 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Universal Foods,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rules Against High Voltage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of Universal Foods Corp. welcomed
Sunday a federal court ruling that upheld his company's defenses
against a hostile $643 million takeover bid by High Voltage
Engineering Corp.
   ``We are pleased with the court's decision,'' said Guy Osborne,
president and chief executive officer of the Milwaukee-based
supplier of food and food ingredients.
   U.S. District Judge Joseph Stadtmueller issued his ruling
Saturday, denying a motion by a High Voltage that sought to
invalidate Wisconsin's anti-takeover law.
   The judge also denied a motion for a preliminary injunction
against Universal's ``poison pill'' defense against takeovers. That
defense would allow Universal shareholders to buy additional shares
of the company at half price if High Voltage were to pursue its bid.
   High Voltage said it had no immediate comment on the ruling.
   Stadtmueller rejected an argument that Universal's directors
violated their duty to shareholders by opposing the takeover and
threatening use of the poison pill.
   ``I find no evidence in the record which convinces me that the
board failed to review this offer in a dispassionate and neutral
manner,'' the judge wrote.
   High Voltage has offered $35 a share for Universal stock, which
closed Friday at $33 in New York Stock Exchange composite trading.
   Universal executives contend a takeover would damage the
company's long-term growth, including its ability to invest in
research and development of new products.
   Universal, based in Milwaukee, is a worldwide supplier of food
and food ingredients, including yeast, cheese, frozen potatoes and
food colorings. It employs about 4,600 people.
</TEXT>
