<HEAD>Dollar Firms, Stock Prices Fall In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar firmed in early trading against the
Japanese yen Monday while stock prices fell.
   The dollar opened trading at 131.88 yen, up 0.81 yen from
Friday's close.
   A dealer with the Bank of Tokyo said the dollar remained firm in
early trading following a strong showing on overseas markets last
Friday.
   In New York, the currency closed last week at 131.68 yen
following a U.S. government report Friday that the nation's producer
price index rose a full percentage point in February, triggering a
new wave of inflation and interest-rate worries.
   There was concern over higher short-term interest rates in the
United States, said the dealer who spoke anonymously.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, a 77.01-point loser last Friday, shed 315.24 points
or 0.9 percent, shortly after the market opened to move to 31,705.77.
</TEXT>
